{"title_page": "Liliya Hrynevych", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup|reason=citations are mostly empty raw text|date=January 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2020}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Liliia Hrynevych\n| native_name         = \u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447\n| native_name_lang    = uk\n| image               = L. Grinevich-1024x719.jpg\n| imagesize           = \n| caption             = \n| office              = [[Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine|Minister of Education and Science]]\n| primeminister       = [[Volodymyr Groysman]]\n| term_start          = 14 April 2016<ref name=\"UNIANnewcab14416\"/>\n| term_end            = 29 August 2019\n| predecessor         = [[Serhiy Kvit]]\n| successor           = [[Hanna Novosad]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1965|5|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Lviv]], [[Ukrainian SSR]], Soviet Union\n| nationality         = [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = \n| party               = [[People's Front (Ukraine)|People's Front]]\n| otherparty          = \n| children            = \n| alma_mater          = [[Lviv University]]\n| website             = \n| awards              = [[Order of Princess Olga]], Badge of the Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine \"Excellence in Education\"\n| signature           = Liliya Hrynevych Signature 2014.png\n| office2             = [[People's Deputy of Ukraine]]\n| convocation2        = [[7th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|7th convocation]]\n| constituency2       = [[Independent (politician)|Independent]], No.14\n| term_start2         = December 12, 2012<ref name=lh7c>[http://itd.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/expage/15646/8 Lilya Hrynevych] at [[Verkhovna Rada]] website</ref>\n| term_end2           = November 27, 2014<ref name=lh7c/>\n| convocation3        = [[8th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|8th convocation]]\n| constituency3       = [[People's Front (Ukraine)|People's Front]], No.9\n| term_start3         = November 27, 2014<ref name=lh8c>[http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/site2/p_deputat?d_id=15646 Lilya Hrynevych] at [[Verkhovna Rada]] website</ref>\n| term_end3           = December 2, 2014<ref name=lh8c/>\n}}\n'''Liliia Mykhailivna Hrynevych''' ({{lang-uk|\u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u0456\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}}, born 13 May 1965){{r|Rada-Bio}} <ref name=\"UNIANnewcab14416\">[http://www.unian.info/politics/1319232-new-cabinet-formed-in-ukraine.html New Cabinet formed in Ukraine], [[UNIAN]] (14 April 2016)</ref>is a Ukrainian educator, politician and civil servant, a Member of the Parliaments of the 7th and 8th Convocation from December 2012 to April 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=.https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/profile/liliya-grinevich-2|title=ednews|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> From April 2016 to August 2019 \u2014the Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine; the\u00a0first woman-Minister of Education and Science in the period of the Ukrainian independence. She has a PHD in Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2006 to 2009, Hrynevych headed the [[Kiev City State Administration]]'s education department.{{r|KP100709}} Representing [[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Fatherland]], she was elected to the 7 convocation of [[Verkhovna Rada]] during the [[2012 Ukrainian parliamentary election]].{{r|MON140425}} Placing 9th on the party list of [[People's Front (Ukraine)|People's Front]], she was re-elected in the [[2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2014 parliamentary election]].She served as the chair of the Parliamentary Committee for Science and Education for two terms (7 and 8 concvocations of Verkhovna Rada).{{r|Rada-Bio}}\n\nFor many years, 1987 to 2002, she worked in secondary education in Ukraine as a teacher, deputy headmistress and headmistress in a number of Lviv schools. She was one of the founders of the Ukrainian Centre for Educational Quality Assessment, of which she was the Director from February to August 2006, focusing her efforts on the development of External Independent Assessment  at a national level. \nHer political career began with the political party \"Front for Change\", as an advisor to party leader Arseniy Yatsenyuk on education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womenua.today/en/liliya-grynevych/|title=Ms. Lilia Hrynevych - Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine|date=2018-11-26|website=\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0416\u0456\u043d\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0439 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In 2012 she was elected as an MP to the Ukrainian Parliament leading the Parliamentary Committee for Science and Education, of which she was the Head until 2016.\nShe has been awarded a Commander of the Order of Princess Olha degree, and has been  awarded an \"Excellence in Education of Ukraine\" medal. She is an Honorary Senator of the [[Ukrainian Catholic University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Life story ==\n\n=== Early years ===\nBorn into a family of teachers, Liliia was 17 years old when she entered Ivan Franko State University of Lviv.She graduated from university in 1987 with the qualification \u201cBiochemist. Lecturer\u201d. Liliia Hrynevych worked as a laboratory assistant from August to November 1987 in the Department of Biochemistry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Later she worked for some time as a tutor during the day in Lviv school No. 70, until  in 1988 she was transferred to Lviv school No. 7 as a biology teacher, where she worked in this capacity until 1992.\n\n'''Career in Education'''\n\nIn 1992 after the independence of Ukraine,  Liliia Hrynevych worked in Lviv at school No. 7, where she was transferred from her role as a biology teacher to that of deputy Headmistress in national education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.info/politics/1319232-new-cabinet-formed-in-ukraine.html|title=New Cabinet formed in Ukraine|website=www.unian.info|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> Liliia was awarded another degree in 1993 with the qualification \u201cEconomist-manager\u201d from the Interdisciplinary Institute for professional training and development at Lviv Polytechnic State University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/profile/liliya-grinevich-2|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>  Liliia researched problems in reforming education systems at internship programs in Warsaw University and Columbia University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \nIn 1994 she moved to Lviv specialized school No. 53, where she worked as deputy director for educational work, while undertaking an intensive course in the study of English. After four years she was transferred to another specialized school in the same city, No. 28, to take on the role of Headmistress, while undertaking an intensive course in the study of German. In this role, the future Minister worked until 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\nIn 2002 Liliia Hrynevych relocated to Kyiv, where she worked at the Krok City Institute of Economics and Law as a senior lecturer in the Department of Management. At the same time, Liliia took on a part-time role as Director of the Renaissance International Fund Centre for Technology in Testing. She participated in the creation of the Ukrainian Centre for Educational Quality Assessment, which she headed during February to August 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://old.kmu.gov.ua/kmu/control/en/publish/article?art_id=38514128&cat_id=244315174|title=Government portal :: New system of secondary school graduates' external testing introduced in Ukraine|website=old.kmu.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> During her work at the Centre, Liliia Hrynevych was deeply involved in the development of External Independent Testing of pupils and applicants to higher education. The result was the introduction of  [[External independent evaluation|External Independent Testing]] ( EIT) at a nationwide level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/profile/liliya-grinevich-2|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\nIn 2005  Liliia Hrynevych presented the thesis on \"Trends in Decentralization of Basic Education Management in Modern Poland\" and obtained [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in Pedagogy, specialty 13.00.01 \u2013 General Pedagogy and History of Pedagogy. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n* During 2006-2009 worked as Head of the Department of Education and Science at Kyiv City State Administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/profile/liliya-grinevich-2|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>                                                                                                2008-2012 \u2013 Lecturer at the Institute of Leadership in Educational Legislation and Policy at Borys Grinchenko Kyiv University, Senior Researcher at the Institute of Pedagogical and Adult Education of the [[National Academy of Educational Sciences of Ukraine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n* 2012-2016 \u2013 Member of Parliament of Ukraine of VII-VIII convocations, Chairman of the Committee on Science and Education.\n* 2016-2019 Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/education-minister-aims-build-new-school-system.html|title=Education minister aims to build new school system - Apr. 27, 2017|date=2017-04-27|website=KyivPost|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* Since november 2019 \u2013 Vice-Rector for Academic and International Affairs of [[Borys Hrinchenko Kyiv University|Borys Grinchenko Kyiv University]].\n\n== MP activity ==\n\n'''<big>7th convocation of Parliament</big>'''\n\nAt the time of the Parliamentary Elections in 2012 she was studying as a doctoral student at the Institute of Teacher Education and Adult Education of the National Academy of Pedagogical Science of Ukraine. In autumn 2012, following the elections to the Verkhovna Rada (Ukrainian Parliament), Liliia Mikhaylivna Hrynevych was elected an MP of Ukraine to the 7th convocation as No. 14 in the list of the United All-Ukrainian \u201c[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchina]]\u201d (Fatherland)  Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://static.rada.gov.ua/site/eng/dep/list.html|title=Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=static.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn December of that year, after election to Parliament, she Headed the Committee on Science and Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.info/politics/732283-vr-approved-chairmen-of-main-committees.html|title=VR approved chairmen of main committees|website=www.unian.info|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> After her appointment to this position Liliia Hrynevych defined the key tasks in this role as: ensuring fair and equitable access to higher education, increased access to education and improvements in its quality. In particular, improving legislation on these matters. At that time a new version of the law on higher education in Ukraine was being drafted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/73337.html|title=News 2 - The Committee on Science and Education held hearings \u201cOn legislative support to higher education development in Ukraine\u201d - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/92943.html|title=News 2 - The Committee on Science and Education recommends that the Parliament adopt in the second reading the draft law \u201cOn Higher Education\u201d - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> On 15  June 2013,  after the amalgamation of the [[Front for Change (Ukraine)|Front for Change]] and [[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchina]] parties, she became one of the deputy leaders of the new Batkivshchina  Party. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.info/politics/1319232-new-cabinet-formed-in-ukraine.html|title=New Cabinet formed in Ukraine|website=www.unian.info|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>   That same year Liliia  joined several newly created parliamentary groups and associations. In particular, parliamentary groups on interparliamentary relations with countries such as Israel, Italy, Canada, South Korea, Poland, Russia, Singapore, the United States, Turkey, Hungary, and Finland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itd.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/expage/15646/8|title=\u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|website=itd.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the creation of a Parliamentary Commission for Future Affairs was proposed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wz.lviv.ua/news/34827-liliia-hrynevych-proponuie-stvoryty-pry-verkhovnii-radi-komisiiu-z-pytan-maibutnoho|title=\u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043d\u0443\u0454 \u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438 \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0456\u0439 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0456 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0441\u0456\u044e \u0437 \u043f\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u044c \u043c\u0430\u0439\u0431\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u2014 \u0412\u0438\u0441\u043e\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0417\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043a|date=2013-06-03|website=wz.lviv.ua|language=uk-ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The task before this committee, as it was seen, should have been in helping MPs to consider issues related to forecasts and future plans, identify priority areas for technological innovation and innovative development of the nation, process models for future development, and to  analyze various government programs.During this convocation of the Parliament of Ukraine, on 22 April 2015, a temporary Commission of the Parliament of Ukraine of the issues of the Future was created. 228 MPs were in favour of this Regulation  No. 2219 on the second reading. Liliia Hrynevych was on the Commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zakon.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/353-VIII|website=zakon.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n'''<big>8th Convocation of Parliament</big>''''\n\nDuring the early parliamentary elections in 2014, Liliia Hrynevych was elected to Parliament on the lists of \"Government Party in Power\" and \"People's Front\", headed at that time by Arseniy Yatsenyuk.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://euromaidanpress.com/2014/09/11/yatseniuk-leads-new-front-line-block-which-may-unite-with-the-presidents/|title=Yatseniuk leads new \u2018front line\u2019 bloc, may unite with the President\u2019s party|last=Developed.\"|first=Government Authorities or Not Fully|date=2014-09-11|website=Euromaidan Press|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Liliia Hrynevych ran on a multi-mandate platform, and was ranked ninth in the list of the party[8].\nIn the 8th convocation Parliament (Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine), Liliia Hrynevych continued working  as a Chair of the Parliament Committee on Science and Education on developing legislative initiatives that enabled reforms in the national system of education including the academic research field.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mportal.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/117223.html|title=Verkhovna Rada Committee on Science and Education establishes workgroup to adapt draft law on science and scientific-technological activities|website=mportal.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/95554.html|title=News 2 - Parliamentary hearings entitled \u201cOn the state and legislative support to the development of science and sci-tech sphere of the state\u201d were held in the Verkhovna Rada on July 2, 2014 - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Liliia Hrynevych co-chaired an Equal Opportunities inter-factional union created in the 8th convocation Parliament in December 2014. Liliia H. was a co-author of the Draft Law on Amendments to Legal Acts of Ukraine, in particular, a gender equality legislative initiative on equal rights and opportunities for women and men in the election process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mportal.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/108231.html|title=Head of Verkhovna Rada Committee for Science and Education and co-head of Rivni Mozhlyvosti interfaction association Liliya Hrynevych takes part in conference entitled|website=mportal.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>  On 14 April 2016, the Verkhovna Rada Parliament of Ukraine appointed  a new [[Government of Ukraine|Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine]], which included Liliia Hrynevych designated as Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/news/248958685|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine appointed new Cabinet of Ministers with Volodymyr Groysman as Prime Minister of Ukraine|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nHrynevych took part in the July [[2019 Ukrainian parliamentary election]] with the party [[Ukrainian Strategy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/592382.html|title=Ukrainian Strategy Party decides to run in parliamentary elections, confirms candidates, program|website=Interfax-Ukraine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> But in the election this party did get not enough votes to clear the 5% election threshold and thus won no parliamentary seats.\n\n=== Legislative contributions ===\nLiliia Hrynevych has initiated three fundamental reforms in the education and social-humanitarian spheres: the [[External independent evaluation|External Independent Testing]], the new Law of Ukraine \u201cOn Higher Education\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zakon.rada.gov.ua/laws/anot/en/1556-18|website=zakon.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/97583.html|title=News 2 - Chairperson of the Committee on Science and Education Liliia Hrynevych participated in the meeting of chairpersons of higher educational institutions of Ukraine on matters of implementation of the Law \u201cOn Higher Education\u201d - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>,aimed at reforming the national tertiary education and \u201cNew Ukrainian School\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/education-minister-aims-build-new-school-system.html|title=Education minister aims to build new school system - Apr. 27, 2017|date=2017-04-27|website=KyivPost|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \u2013 a reform of the general secondary education defined by the Law of Ukraine \u201cOn education \u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zakon.rada.gov.ua/laws/anot/en/1556-18|website=zakon.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>  Implementation of External Independent Testing has led to equal access to education for everyone as well as a reduction in [[Corruption in Ukraine|corruption in education in Ukraine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womenua.today/en/liliya-grynevych/|title=Ms. Lilia Hrynevych - Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine|date=2018-11-26|website=\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0416\u0456\u043d\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0439 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The Higher Education Law of Ukraine in 2014 established many innovations in higher education in Ukraine. In particular, this autonomy of universities, increased roles for student unions, changes in educational levels and academic degrees according to international practice, a new classification of universities, and new financing higher education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/article/content/ukraine-politics/rada-adopts-law-to-reform-higher-education-354346.html|title=Rada adopts law to reform higher education - Jul. 02, 2014|date=2014-07-02|website=KyivPost|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/97583.html|title=News 2 - Chairperson of the Committee on Science and Education Liliia Hrynevych participated in the meeting of chairpersons of higher educational institutions of Ukraine on matters of implementation of the Law \u201cOn Higher Education\u201d - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe main developers of higher education reform in Ukraine in general and the Higher Education law have been, in addition to Liliia Hrynevych as the Chairman of Parliamentary Committee  of Ukraine on Science and Education considered to be key include the former Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine, [[Serhiy Kvit]], and the developer of the first draft of the new law, Member of the [[National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine|National Academy of Science of Ukraine]] and [[Rector (academia)|Rector]] of [[Igor Sikorsky Kyiv Polytechnic Institute|Kyiv Polytechnic Institute]], [[Mykhailo Zghurovsky|Mykhaylo Zghurovsky]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uacrisis.org/8971-sergijj-kvit-2|title=Serhiy Kvit: The Law \u201cOn Higher Education\u201d is adopted, next are the laws \u201cOn Education\u201d and \u201cOn sciences and research-and-development activities\u201d {{!}} UACRISIS.ORG|date=2014-09-05|website=Ukraine crisis media center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Liliia Hrynevych initiated changes to the science management system, enshrined in the Law on Scientific and Technical Activities,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schiermeier|first=Quirin|date=2016-03-03|title=Conflicting laws threaten Ukrainian science|url=http://www.nature.com/news/conflicting-laws-threaten-ukrainian-science-1.19470|journal=Nature News|language=en|volume=531|issue=7592|pages=18|doi=10.1038/531018a}}</ref> which was supported by 235 parliamentarians in November 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/120487.html|title=News - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopts Law \"On scientific and scientific-technological activities\" - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The Law, in particular, defines legal, administrative and financial foundations for developments in the Scientific and Technical sphere. The Law also establishes the National Council for Science and Technology Development and the National Research Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mportal.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/117223.html|title=Verkhovna Rada Committee on Science and Education establishes workgroup to adapt draft law on science and scientific-technological activities|website=mportal.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The drafting and adoption of the Law on Education made it possible to launch \u2018The New Ukrainian School\u2019, the reform of general secondary education. It was under the chairmanship of Liliia Hrynevych, that the draft Committee prepared the Draft Law on Education and sent it to the Parliament for re-reading in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/123991.html|title=News - Elaboration of draft framework law on education being finalized - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=www.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mon.gov.ua/ua/news/usi-novivni-interview-2016-11-02-schools-to-drive-democracy-change-in-ukraine|title=\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0456\u0442\u0438 \u0456 \u043d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 |trans-title=Schools to drive democracy change in Ukraine|last=Kitsoft|website=mon.gov.ua|language=uk|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In 2017 the document was finalized and adopted in the second reading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/149413.html|title=News - Ukraine\u2019s law \u201cOn Education\u201d out now - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=www.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Among other achievements - the adoption of amendments to the Budget Code, and changes related to the organization of inclusive education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/102209.html|title=News 2 - The Committee on Science and Education discussed the issue of consideration of Committee\u2019s proposals on allocation of expenditures of the State Budget of Ukraine for 2015 - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nDuring her tenure during the 7th convocation,  Liliia Hrynevych introduced 110 Bills and resolutions, 14 of which have entered into force, and submitted 23 parliamentary inquiries. The total includes 261 amendments to Bills, of which 244 have been adopted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/pt2/reports.dep2?PERSON=15646&SKL=8|title=\u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|website=w1.c1.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/zweb2/wcadr42d?sklikannja=8&kod8011=15646|title=\u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|website=w1.c1.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> During her tenure during the 8th convocation Liliia Hrynevych has introduced 82 bills and resolutions, 37 of which have entered into force, and submitted 10 parliamentary inquiries. The total included 52 amendments to Bills of which 34 have been adopted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/pt2/reports.dep2?PERSON=15646&SKL=9|title=\u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|website=w1.c1.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/zweb2/wcadr42d?sklikannja=9&kod8011=15646|title=\u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|website=w1.c1.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              \n\n== Activity as Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine (April 2016 -August 2019)                                                                                                                                                                      ==\nDevelopment of the education system\u00a0 \u00a0was a priority\u00a0 of\u00a0 \u00a0Volodymyr Groysman\u2019s government. Over the three years of Liliia Hrynevych\u2019s work in the Government, the consolidated budget for education\u00a0 increased from [[Ukrainian hryvnia|UAH]] 129.4 billion to [[Ukrainian hryvnia|UAH]] 246 billion. Particular attention was paid to rising the salaries in the education sector. From 2016 to 2019, teacher salaries\u00a0 increased by over 80%.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/storage/app/media/reform%20office/Ukraine_Reform_Conference_II_web.pdf|title=ref pac|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In pre-school education, the priority was to eliminate the waiting lists for enrolment to kindergartens.\u00a0 Co-operation with local authorities made it possible to shorten the wating lists from 96,000 seats in 2016 to 33,600 in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/news/novi-mozhlivosti-ta-resursi-vid-decentralizaciyi-potribno-vkladati-v-usi-sferi-rozvitku-regioniv-i-peredusim-osvitu-volodimir-grojsman|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Volodymyr Groysman: New opportunities and resources offered by decentralization need to be invested in all regional development sectors|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nLiliia Hrynevych led \"The New Ukrainian School\" (NUS) - a large-scale reform in general secondary education. Liliia Hrynevych was a co-author of the New Ukrainian School Concept, which defined the principles and objectives of the reform.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://mon.gov.ua/storage/app/media/zagalna%20serednya/Book-ENG.pdf|title=common ed pack|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/news/249248984|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Lilia Hrynevych presented a New Ukrainian School concept: We don't need to adjust the system, we should achieve new results instead|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, the Government approved the Policy Proposal to reform the general secondary education. The reform aimed at transition from a \"knowledge only school\" to a \"school of competencies\", that is the ability to use the obtained knowledge to solve practical problems and form value-based relationships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukraineworld.org/articles/reforms/ukrainian-education-new-era|title=Ukrainian Education in the New Era|website=ukraineworld.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nMinister Liliia Hrynevych suggested implementing the NUS reform in three directions: updating the education content; targeted teacher training; updating the educational environment (purchase of mobile desks, new equipment and training materials).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/education-minister-aims-build-new-school-system.html?cn-reloaded=1|title=updating school system|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n\nThe preparation and implementation of the reform began in 2017 with 100 schools in Ukraine starting to pilot the new programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukraineworld.org/articles/reforms/ukrainian-education-new-era|title=Ukrainian Education in the New Era|website=ukraineworld.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>The State Standard for Primary Education was approved In February 2018, and in September that year, all first-graders in the country began the school year in the updated learning envirnment with the\u00a0 teachers using modern teaching methods according to the new State Standard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/reformi/rozvitok-lyudskogo-kapitalu/reforma-osviti|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Education and Science Reform|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nWithin the framework of the reform, nearly 50,000 elementary school teachers, more than 11,000 Principals and Deputy Heads of educational institutions took the online and face-to-face in-service training course in blended mode.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://rakhiv-osvita.gov.ua/en/2018/02/12/%D0%BF%D1%96%D0%B4%D0%B2%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D1%8F-%D0%BA%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%BB%D1%96%D1%84%D1%96%D0%BA%D0%B0%D1%86%D1%96%D1%97-%D0%B2%D1%87%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%B5%D0%BB%D1%96%D0%B2-%D0%BF%D0%BE/|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a voluntary teacher certification was introduced aiming to identify teachers with a high professional level, innovative teaching methods and ability to share their experience. The certified teachers are payed a 20% bonus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://opinionua.com/en/2018/12/17/hobsey-about-new-ukrainian-school/The pilot certification started in 2019. https://www.tellerreport.com/news/2019-11-18---in-ukraine--announced-the-excess-number-of-school-teachers-in-the-country-.SJZA7N5x3H.html|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Government\u00a0 \u00a0subsidized the\u00a0 refurbishment of schools and\u00a0 renovation of the educational environment. The state investments in school infrastructure in 2017 amounted to UAH 1 009.5 mln, in 2018 - UAH 2 509 mln, and in 2019 - UAH 3 886.3 mln.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mon.gov.ua/ua/news/porivnyano-z-2017-m-cogo-roku-investiciyi-v-shkilnu-infrastrukturu-ta-cilovi-subvenciyi-zrosli-majzhe-v-3-razi-liliya-grinevich-pid-chas-zvitu-uryadu-za-2017-rik|title=\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0456\u0442\u0438 \u0456 \u043d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 - \u041f\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0432\u043d\u044f\u043d\u043e \u0437 2017-\u043c \u0446\u044c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u043e\u043a\u0443 \u0456\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0446\u0456\u0457 \u0432 \u0448\u043a\u0456\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0443 \u0456\u043d\u0444\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0443 \u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0456\u043b\u044c\u043e\u0432\u0456 \u0441\u0443\u0431\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0456\u0457 \u0437\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u043c\u0430\u0439\u0436\u0435 \u0432 3 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438, \u2013 \u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u043f\u0456\u0434 \u0447\u0430\u0441 \u0437\u0432\u0456\u0442\u0443 \u0423\u0440\u044f\u0434\u0443 \u0437\u0430 2017 \u0440\u0456\u043a|last=Kitsoft|website=mon.gov.ua|language=uk|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://mon.gov.ua/storage/app/media/Serpneva%20conferentcia/2019/mon18-06-2019conference-fin-grinevich.pdf|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe funds were allocated to the priority areas such as\u00a0 elementary school classroom transformation, equipment for the science and mathematics classrooms, the\u00a0 Ukrainian language classrooms in minority language schools,\u00a0 school sports complexes, equipment for the computer classes and the Internet access.\n\nThe learning conditions for the students in rural areas was\u00a0 a special\u00a0 concern for the Ministry. To improve these, a hub school network was created in May 2019. 785 hub schools and 1,272 hub school branches were established to build up the network in Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/default/files/2019-09-24-UkraineDecentralization.pdf|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>                                                                                                                                                                     The hub schools and their brances were assigned a priority of establishing modern science, math and computer classes, and transportation of the children from remote villages by school buses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decentralization.gov.ua/en/news/7657|title=Liliya Hrynevych: 25% of labour population in cities of oblast significance and AHs work in educational sector|last=Author|website=decentralization.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Coordination Council was established to promote collaboration between the local executive and self-governing bodies and ensure a more effective co-operation between the regional state administrations, local communities and other agencies in the course of the NUS\u00a0 implementation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/news/reforma-osviti-nadast-dodatkovih-perevag-u-virishenni-problemi-trudovoyi-migraciyi-volodimir-grojsman|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Volodymyr Groysman: Education reform will give additional preferences in solving labor migration issues|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nLiliia Hrynevychformed an ecosystem of organizations with shared concepts of the reform ideas on the partnership pedagogy, lifelong learning, competency-based and learner-centered\u00a0 approaches to learning and teaching, etc. A number of non-governmental organizations, including EdCampUkraine, EdEra, Ukrainian Step by Step Foundation (USSF), Osvitoria, Smart Osvita , BatkiSOS and others, joined this ecosystem .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edcamp.org.ua/inmediaeng|title=EdCamp Ukraine {{!}} \u0423 \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0456\u0430|website=edcamp|language=ru|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ussf.kiev.ua/|title=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u00bb|website=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u00bb|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://osvitoria.org/en/project/spivpratsya-z-ministerstvom-osvity-ukrayiny/|website=osvitoria.org|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ussf.kiev.ua/|title=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u00bb|website=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u00bb|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.smart-osvita.org/|title=Home|website=en.smart-osvita.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nTo implement the reform, Minister Liliia Hrynevych build up cooperative relationships\u00a0 with international partners. In particular, the large-scale Finnish-Ukrainian project \u201cLearning together\u201d attracted \u20ac 6 million to assist\u00a0 the implementation of the NUS reform priorities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://um.fi/news/-/asset_publisher/GRSnUwaHDPv5/content/suomi-mukana-ukrainan-koulu-uudistukses-1|title=Finland takes part in Ukrainian school reform|website=Ministry for Foreign Affairs|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Memorandum signed between the Ministry of Education and Science and the [[The Lego Group|LEGO Foundation]], made it possible to provide every Ukrainian first-grader and every class with\u00a0 free [[Lego|LEGO]] kits to support introduction of the game - and activity-based learning into the educational process.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.legofoundation.com/en/about-us/focus-geographies/ukraine/Liliia Hrynevych\u00a0 started negotiations with the World Bank to help accelerate the implementation of the primary and secondary school reform|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mon.gov.ua/eng/news/senior-specialized-school-network-formation-one-main-challenges-new-ukrainian-school-reform-and-we-are-already-looking-partners-mission-liliya-hrynevych-meeting-world-bank-representatives|title=Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine - Senior specialized school network formation is one of the main challenges of the New Ukrainian School reform, and we are already looking for partners for this mission, \u2013 Liliya Hrynevych at the meeting with the World Bank representatives|last=Kitsoft|website=mon.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nAn important area of\u00a0 the Ministry of Education and Science activity was development of inclusive education carried out in cooperation with [[Maryna Poroshenko]], the Head of the Poroshenko Charitable Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-society/2667214-inclusive-education-poroshenko-foundation-google-ukraine-education-ministry-sign-memorandum.html|title=Inclusive education: Poroshenko Foundation, Google Ukraine, Education Ministry sign Memorandum. Photos|website=www.ukrinform.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Between 2016 and 2018, the number of children with special educational needs who enrolled in secondary schools increased from 2 720<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://fsr.org.ua/sites/default/files/imce/book_print.pdf)\u00a0|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> to 12 000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukraineworld.org/articles/ukraine-explained/steady-track-inclusive-education-what-has-ukraine-done-so-far..%20561|title=Article [U/W]|website=ukraineworld.org|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Inclusive Resource Centers were set up to assist parents and teachers in creating an individual development program for each child with special educational needs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-society/2736547-561-resource-centers-for-inclusive-education-operate-in-ukraine.html|title=561 resource centers for inclusive education operate in Ukraine|website=www.ukrinform.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nAs Minister, Liliia Hrynevych launched an active [[Anti-bullying legislation|anti-bullying campaign]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://ukraine.savethechildren.net/article/how-protect-education-attack-ukrainian-context|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>The campaign found its support in the Law passed by the [[Verkhovna Rada|Parliament.]] The Law provides for counteracting bullying and introduces administrative penalties for [[bullying]] during the educational process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/rada-introduces-fines-for-bullying-in-schools.html|title=Rada introduces fines for bullying in schools {{!}} KyivPost - Ukraine's Global Voice|date=2018-12-19|website=KyivPost|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Additionally, the new Law on Education introduces the Institute of Educational Ombudsmen to ensure the students\u2019, educators\u2019, and scholars\u2019 rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opinionua.com/en/2019/09/02/serhii-horbachov/|title=Opinion {{!}} Serhii Horbachov: how Education Ombudsman service will function, whom and how it will protect and how much money is allocated for its activity|date=2019-09-02|website=Opinion|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Law on Education adopted in September 2017 laid down the main provisions of the educational reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://studyinukraine.in.ua/a-new-law-of-ukraine-on-education/|title=A new Law of Ukraine On education \u2013 Study in Ukraine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The adoption of the Law was followed by an extensive discussions of Article 7, which specifies the state language in the education system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lnu.edu.ua/en/at-lviv-university-minister-of-education-and-science-of-ukraine-tells-about-language-issue-in-law-on-education/|title=AT LVIV UNIVERSITY, MINISTER OF EDUCATION AND SCIENCE OF UKRAINE TELLS ABOUT LANGUAGE ISSUE IN LAW ON EDUCATION|website=Ivan Franko National University of Lviv|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>The state leaders of [[President of Romania|Romania]] and [[Prime Minister of Hungary|Hungary]] claimed the language article of the Law\u00a0 restricted the rights of the national minorities in Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/f1d66aac1b9c486386a138a0a0ca6b43|title=Hungary, Ukraine still at odds over Ukraine education law|date=2017-10-12|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nUkraine addressed the [[Venice Commission|European Commission for Democracy through Law (Venice Commission)]] and asked for its Opinion. In December 2017, when the Venice Commission was considering the legitimacy of Article 7, Liliia Hrynevychprovided convincing arguments and successfully defended the article \"Language of Education\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-society/2363679-ukraine-not-to-change-language-article-of-education-law-minister.html|title=Ukraine not to change language article of education law - minister|website=www.ukrinform.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>In July 2019, the [[Constitutional Court of Ukraine]] recognized the constitutionality of the Law on Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.ccu.gov.ua/en/docs/2541?order=created&sort=desc|title=2019 {{!}} Constitutional Court of Ukraine|website=web.ccu.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nPursuant to the Law on Education, the State Service for Education Quality (SSEQ)was established in 2017, which is responsible for upholding\u00a0 the state education standards and ensuring the proper education quality\u00a0 under the decentralized conditions. The basic principle of its activity is to assist educational institutions, management, teachers in improving the quality of their activities as well as\u00a0 the quality of the student learning outcomes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reformsguide.org.ua/news/the-state-service-of-education-quality-established-in-ukraine/|title=The State Service of Education Quality Established in Ukraine|date=2017-12-07|website=The Reforms Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nModernization of vocational education became an important priority of the Ministry's activities under the guidance of Liliia Hrynevych. The implementation of the investment program in 2016-2018 made it possible to create 100 training and practical centers\u00a0 for the most acute professions, where students can learn to work with modern materials, equipment and technologies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/reformi/rozvitok-lyudskogo-kapitalu/reforma-osviti|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Education and Science Reform|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe\u00a0 Agreement on financing the EU4Skills Project: Best Skills for Modern Ukraine was signed between Ukraine and the European Commission In 2018. The project attracted [[Euro|EUR]] 58 million in total and aims to\u00a0 create a network of Professional Excellence Centers,\u00a0 \u00a0including purchase of new equipment, professional development of masters and teachers, development of new curricula and standards for students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mon.gov.ua/eng/news/yevropa-nadaye-58-mln-yevro-na-modernizaciyu-profesijnoyi-osviti-v-ukrayini-v-bryusseli-pidpisano-ugodu-pro-finansuvannya-proektu-eu4skills|title=Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine - European Commission to allocate EUR 58 million to modernize vocational education in Ukraine|last=Kitsoft|website=mon.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nDuring her time in office, Minister Liliia Hrynevychmodernised the system of admission to higher education institutions.\u00a0 The admission is based on external independent testing (ZNO) results and the entire procedure is carried out online on the principle \u2018an offer goes to the best candidate\u2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chmnu.edu.ua/36733-2/|title=\u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u043f\u0440\u043e \u043f\u0456\u0434\u0441\u0443\u043c\u043a\u0438 \u0432\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u043a\u0430\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0457-2019 - \u0427\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u043d\u0456\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442 \u0456\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0456 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u041c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0438|date=2019-08-07|website=\u0427\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u043d\u0456\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442 \u0456\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0456  \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u041c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0438|language=ru|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> A mandatory standard entrance exam is introduced as secondary admission criteria for the\u00a0 Law and International Law cources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/reformi/rozvitok-lyudskogo-kapitalu/reforma-osviti|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Education and Science Reform|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The National Agency for Higher Education Quality Assurance<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://en.naqa.gov.ua/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/NAHEQA-Ukraine.pdfwas established|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, Higher education competency based standards were developed for 266 specialisms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journalist.today/en/ukraine-approves-100-modern-standards-of-higher-education-hrynevych/|title=Ukraine approves 100 modern standards of higher education \u2013 Hrynevych|last=\u0412\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0443\u043d|first=\u041a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044f\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d|date=2019-07-15|website=Journalist.today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nMinister Liliia Hrynevychpaid special attention to the reseach development at university.\u00a0For the first time the government funded a program aimed to create\u00a0 \u00a0centers for collective use of reseach equipment at higher education institutions.\u00a0 Establishment of eight\u00a0 centers at Ukrainian universities was funded by the state budget in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://ri-links2ua.eu/object/news/674In 2019, university reseach received its first basic funding.|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLiliia Hrynevychinitiated transformation of the scientific research management and financing system. In 2017\u20132018, the budgetary funding of science and research\u00a0 managed by the Ministry increased by 69%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/160685.html|title=News - \u2018Ask the Government\u2019 hour - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>The National Council for Science and TechnologyDevelopment began its work which made impact on the policy-making in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://frontnews.eu/news/en/38209|title=Hrynevych: \u201cUkraine occupies a not very high place in the international innovation rating\u201d|website=FrontNews|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Ukrainian National Research Foundation was launched to be at the forefront of the new funding system, in particular in\u00a0 provision of research grants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mon.gov.ua/eng/news/ukrayina-ta-nimechchina-domovilisya-pro-stvorennya-spilnih-centriv-peredovih-doslidzhen|title=Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine - Ukraine and Germany to establish joint centers for front-rank technologies|last=Kitsoft|website=mon.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the Ministry of Education and Science first financed the access of the Ukrainian universities and research institutions\u00a0 to [[Scopus]] and the [[Web of Science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/reformi/rozvitok-lyudskogo-kapitalu/reforma-osviti|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Education and Science Reform|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>In 2019 these scientometric bases were available for all state budgeted universities and scientific institutions at the state budget costs.\n\nStarting in 2018, the Antarctic research at [[Vernadsky Research Base|\u201cAkademik Vernadsky\u201d]], a Ukrainian polar station,\u00a0 intensified. The National Antarctic Scientific Center\u00a0 headed by Evgen Dykyi, a marine ecology researcher and Ukrainian activist, renewed its full membership in the [[Scientific Committee on Antarctic Research]], modernized the station, provided high-quality Internet and communication; Ukrainian women joined the expedition for the first time in 20 years on the mainland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uac.gov.ua/en/women-antarctic-hryvnia-and-fully-domestic-outfit-the-24th-uae-left-for-the-akademik-vernadsky-station/|title=Women, Antarctic hryvnia and fully domestic outfit. The 24th UAE left for the Akademik Vernadsky station|last=\u041e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0430|first=\u0417\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0447|date=2019-03-26|website=UAC|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://day.kyiv.ua/en/article/topic-day/ukraine-antarctica-new-era|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe National Qualification Agency, a collegial body for implementation of the state qualification policy, was established to ensure development of the National Qualification System and compliance of the learning outcomes with the relevant education levels, qualifications and the modern market requirements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://connections.etf.europa.eu/wikis/home?lang=en#!/wiki/Wf591e43b607e_4ccf_8d94_a3256a255147/page/Ukraine%20-%20NQF%20inventory|title=Welcome to Wikis|website=connections.etf.europa.eu|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAs described by Liliia herself, she met her future husband Mykhaylo during their student years, when Liliia was involved in student activities. In particular, she sang in the \u2018Cheremosh\u2019 student group.\n\nShe speaks English and Polish.\n\nAccording to politrada.com, Liliia Hryevych is most closely associated with Arseniy Yatsenyuk.[36] .Liliia Hrynevych began her political career when she joined the \"Front for Change\" party, which for a short time had her on the Board of the party. She coordinated the direction of the \"Knowledge Society\" part of a project called \"Government of Change\"  for this party, on behalf of party leader Arseniy Yatsenyuk, for whom she was the adviser on Education Affairs  for \"Front for Change\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://file.liga.net/persons/grinevich-liliya|title=\u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f|website=LIGA|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n\n* Badge \u201cExcellence in Education of Ukraine\u201d;\n* Badge \u201cExcellence in Capital Education\u201d;\n* Honorary diploma of Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine \"For Merit to the Ukrainian people\";\n* Order of Princess Olga 3rd Class \"for significant personal contribution to the development of national science, strengthening of scientific and technical potential of Ukraine, diligent work and high professionalism\";\n* [[Honorary title (academic)|Honorary Professor]] at [[Borys Hrinchenko Kyiv University|Borys Grinchenko Kyiv University]] \"for active civic position, personal contribution to the development of the University, creation of a holistic system of training and professional development of academic staff in Kyiv\";\n* Honorary Senator at the [[Ukrainian Catholic University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=Rada-Bio>{{cite web |url= http://gapp.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/page/15646 |title= \u041d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 VIII \u0441\u043a\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f: \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u0456\u0432\u043d\u0430 |language= Ukrainian |trans-title= Eighth convocation members of the Verkhovna Rada: Liliya Mykhailivna Hrynevych |publisher= [[Verkhovna Rada]] |access-date= 2015-01-07 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160927082251/http://gapp.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/page/15646 |archive-date= 2016-09-27 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=KP100709>{{cite news |url= http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/ukraine-school-system-steps-from-europe-back-to-ru-72767.html |title= Ukraine school system steps from Europe back to Russia |first= Yuriy |last= Onyshkiv |work= [[Kyiv Post]] |date= 9 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=MON140425>{{cite news|url=http://mon.gov.ua/en/regionalnews/32082-liliya-hrynevych,-chair-of-the-parliamentary-committee-for-science-and-education,-meets-with-academics-and-the-public-in-mykolayiv |title=Liliya Hrynevych, Chair of the Parliamentary Committee for Science and Education, meets with academics and the public in Mykolayiv |publisher=Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine |date=25 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703191806/http://mon.gov.ua/en/regionalnews/32082-liliya-hrynevych%2C-chair-of-the-parliamentary-committee-for-science-and-education%2C-meets-with-academics-and-the-public-in-mykolayiv |archivedate= 3 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Ministers of Education and Sciences of Ukraine}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hrynevych, Liliya}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lviv]]\n[[Category:Seventh convocation members of the Verkhovna Rada]]\n[[Category:Eighth convocation members of the Verkhovna Rada]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:People's Front (Ukraine) politicians]]\n[[Category:Lviv Polytechnic alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Lviv alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ukrainian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ukrainian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Education and science ministers of Ukraine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup|reason=citations are mostly empty raw text|date=January 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2020}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Liliia Hrynevych\n| native_name         = \u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447\n| native_name_lang    = uk\n| image               = L. Grinevich-1024x719.jpg\n| imagesize           = \n| caption             = \n| office              = [[Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine|Minister of Education and Science]]\n| primeminister       = [[Volodymyr Groysman]]\n| term_start          = 14 April 2016<ref name=\"UNIANnewcab14416\"/>\n| term_end            = 29 August 2019\n| predecessor         = [[Serhiy Kvit]]\n| successor           = [[Hanna Novosad]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1965|5|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Lviv]], [[Ukrainian SSR]], Soviet Union\n| nationality         = [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = \n| party               = [[People's Front (Ukraine)|People's Front]]\n| otherparty          = \n| children            = \n| alma_mater          = [[Lviv University]]\n| website             = \n| awards              = [[Order of Princess Olga]], Badge of the Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine \"Excellence in Education\"\n| signature           = Liliya Hrynevych Signature 2014.png\n| office2             = [[People's Deputy of Ukraine]]\n| convocation2        = [[7th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|7th convocation]]\n| constituency2       = [[Independent (politician)|Independent]], No.14\n| term_start2         = December 12, 2012<ref name=lh7c>[http://itd.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/expage/15646/8 Lilya Hrynevych] at [[Verkhovna Rada]] website</ref>\n| term_end2           = November 27, 2014<ref name=lh7c/>\n| convocation3        = [[8th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|8th convocation]]\n| constituency3       = [[People's Front (Ukraine)|People's Front]], No.9\n| term_start3         = November 27, 2014<ref name=lh8c>[http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/site2/p_deputat?d_id=15646 Lilya Hrynevych] at [[Verkhovna Rada]] website</ref>\n| term_end3           = December 2, 2014<ref name=lh8c/>\n}}\n'''Liliia Mykhailivna Hrynevych''' ({{lang-uk|\u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u0456\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}}, born 13 May 1965){{r|Rada-Bio}} <ref name=\"UNIANnewcab14416\">[http://www.unian.info/politics/1319232-new-cabinet-formed-in-ukraine.html New Cabinet formed in Ukraine], [[UNIAN]] (14 April 2016)</ref>is a Ukrainian educator, politician and civil servant, a Member of the Parliaments of the 7th and 8th Convocation from December 2012 to April 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=.https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/profile/liliya-grinevich-2|title=ednews|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> From April 2016 to August 2019 \u2014the Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine; the\u00a0first woman-Minister of Education and Science in the period of the Ukrainian independence. She has a PHD in Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2006 to 2009, Hrynevych headed the [[Kiev City State Administration]]'s education department.{{r|KP100709}} Representing [[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Fatherland]], she was elected to the 7 convocation of [[Verkhovna Rada]] during the [[2012 Ukrainian parliamentary election]].{{r|MON140425}} Placing 9th on the party list of [[People's Front (Ukraine)|People's Front]], she was re-elected in the [[2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election|2014 parliamentary election]].She served as the chair of the Parliamentary Committee for Science and Education for two terms (7 and 8 concvocations of Verkhovna Rada).{{r|Rada-Bio}}\n\nFor many years, 1987 to 2002, she worked in secondary education in Ukraine as a teacher, deputy headmistress and headmistress in a number of Lviv schools. She was one of the founders of the Ukrainian Centre for Educational Quality Assessment, of which she was the Director from February to August 2006, focusing her efforts on the development of External Independent Assessment  at a national level. \nHer political career began with the political party \"Front for Change\", as an advisor to party leader Arseniy Yatsenyuk on education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womenua.today/en/liliya-grynevych/|title=Ms. Lilia Hrynevych - Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine|date=2018-11-26|website=\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0416\u0456\u043d\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0439 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In 2012 she was elected as an MP to the Ukrainian Parliament leading the Parliamentary Committee for Science and Education, of which she was the Head until 2016.\nShe has been awarded a Commander of the Order of Princess Olha degree, and has been  awarded an \"Excellence in Education of Ukraine\" medal. She is an Honorary Senator of the [[Ukrainian Catholic University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Life story ==\n\n=== Early years ===\nBorn into a family of teachers, Liliia was 17 years old when she entered Ivan Franko State University of Lviv.She graduated from university in 1987 with the qualification \u201cBiochemist. Lecturer\u201d. Liliia Hrynevych worked as a laboratory assistant from August to November 1987 in the Department of Biochemistry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Later she worked for some time as a tutor during the day in Lviv school No. 70, until  in 1988 she was transferred to Lviv school No. 7 as a biology teacher, where she worked in this capacity until 1992.\n\n'''Career in Education'''\n\nIn 1992 after the independence of Ukraine,  Liliia Hrynevych worked in Lviv at school No. 7, where she was transferred from her role as a biology teacher to that of deputy Headmistress in national education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.info/politics/1319232-new-cabinet-formed-in-ukraine.html|title=New Cabinet formed in Ukraine|website=www.unian.info|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> Liliia was awarded another degree in 1993 with the qualification \u201cEconomist-manager\u201d from the Interdisciplinary Institute for professional training and development at Lviv Polytechnic State University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/profile/liliya-grinevich-2|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>  Liliia researched problems in reforming education systems at internship programs in Warsaw University and Columbia University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \nIn 1994 she moved to Lviv specialized school No. 53, where she worked as deputy director for educational work, while undertaking an intensive course in the study of English. After four years she was transferred to another specialized school in the same city, No. 28, to take on the role of Headmistress, while undertaking an intensive course in the study of German. In this role, the future Minister worked until 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\nIn 2002 Liliia Hrynevych relocated to Kyiv, where she worked at the Krok City Institute of Economics and Law as a senior lecturer in the Department of Management. At the same time, Liliia took on a part-time role as Director of the Renaissance International Fund Centre for Technology in Testing. She participated in the creation of the Ukrainian Centre for Educational Quality Assessment, which she headed during February to August 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://old.kmu.gov.ua/kmu/control/en/publish/article?art_id=38514128&cat_id=244315174|title=Government portal :: New system of secondary school graduates' external testing introduced in Ukraine|website=old.kmu.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> During her work at the Centre, Liliia Hrynevych was deeply involved in the development of External Independent Testing of pupils and applicants to higher education. The result was the introduction of  [[External independent evaluation|External Independent Testing]] ( EIT) at a nationwide level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/profile/liliya-grinevich-2|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\nIn 2005  Liliia Hrynevych presented the thesis on \"Trends in Decentralization of Basic Education Management in Modern Poland\" and obtained [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in Pedagogy, specialty 13.00.01 \u2013 General Pedagogy and History of Pedagogy. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n* During 2006-2009 worked as Head of the Department of Education and Science at Kyiv City State Administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/profile/liliya-grinevich-2|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>                                                                                                2008-2012 \u2013 Lecturer at the Institute of Leadership in Educational Legislation and Policy at Borys Grinchenko Kyiv University, Senior Researcher at the Institute of Pedagogical and Adult Education of the [[National Academy of Educational Sciences of Ukraine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n* 2012-2016 \u2013 Member of Parliament of Ukraine of VII-VIII convocations, Chairman of the Committee on Science and Education.\n* 2016-2019 Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/education-minister-aims-build-new-school-system.html|title=Education minister aims to build new school system - Apr. 27, 2017|date=2017-04-27|website=KyivPost|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n* Since november 2019 \u2013 Vice-Rector for Academic and International Affairs of [[Borys Hrinchenko Kyiv University|Borys Grinchenko Kyiv University]].\n\n== MP activity ==\n\n'''<big>7th convocation of Parliament</big>'''\n\nAt the time of the Parliamentary Elections in 2012 she was studying as a doctoral student at the Institute of Teacher Education and Adult Education of the National Academy of Pedagogical Science of Ukraine. In autumn 2012, following the elections to the Verkhovna Rada (Ukrainian Parliament), Liliia Mikhaylivna Hrynevych was elected an MP of Ukraine to the 7th convocation as No. 14 in the list of the United All-Ukrainian \u201c[[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchina]]\u201d (Fatherland)  Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://static.rada.gov.ua/site/eng/dep/list.html|title=Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=static.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn December of that year, after election to Parliament, she Headed the Committee on Science and Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.info/politics/732283-vr-approved-chairmen-of-main-committees.html|title=VR approved chairmen of main committees|website=www.unian.info|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> After her appointment to this position Liliia Hrynevych defined the key tasks in this role as: ensuring fair and equitable access to higher education, increased access to education and improvements in its quality. In particular, improving legislation on these matters. At that time a new version of the law on higher education in Ukraine was being drafted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/73337.html|title=News 2 - The Committee on Science and Education held hearings \u201cOn legislative support to higher education development in Ukraine\u201d - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/92943.html|title=News 2 - The Committee on Science and Education recommends that the Parliament adopt in the second reading the draft law \u201cOn Higher Education\u201d - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> On 15  June 2013,  after the amalgamation of the [[Front for Change (Ukraine)|Front for Change]] and [[All-Ukrainian Union \"Fatherland\"|Batkivshchina]] parties, she became one of the deputy leaders of the new Batkivshchina  Party. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.info/politics/1319232-new-cabinet-formed-in-ukraine.html|title=New Cabinet formed in Ukraine|website=www.unian.info|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>   That same year Liliia  joined several newly created parliamentary groups and associations. In particular, parliamentary groups on interparliamentary relations with countries such as Israel, Italy, Canada, South Korea, Poland, Russia, Singapore, the United States, Turkey, Hungary, and Finland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itd.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/expage/15646/8|title=\u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|website=itd.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the creation of a Parliamentary Commission for Future Affairs was proposed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wz.lviv.ua/news/34827-liliia-hrynevych-proponuie-stvoryty-pry-verkhovnii-radi-komisiiu-z-pytan-maibutnoho|title=\u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043d\u0443\u0454 \u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438 \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0456\u0439 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0456 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0441\u0456\u044e \u0437 \u043f\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u044c \u043c\u0430\u0439\u0431\u0443\u0442\u043d\u044c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u2014 \u0412\u0438\u0441\u043e\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0417\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043a|date=2013-06-03|website=wz.lviv.ua|language=uk-ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The task before this committee, as it was seen, should have been in helping MPs to consider issues related to forecasts and future plans, identify priority areas for technological innovation and innovative development of the nation, process models for future development, and to  analyze various government programs.During this convocation of the Parliament of Ukraine, on 22 April 2015, a temporary Commission of the Parliament of Ukraine of the issues of the Future was created. 228 MPs were in favour of this Regulation  No. 2219 on the second reading. Liliia Hrynevych was on the Commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zakon.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/353-VIII|website=zakon.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n'''<big>8th Convocation of Parliament</big>''''\n\nDuring the early parliamentary elections in 2014, Liliia Hrynevych was elected to Parliament on the lists of \"Government Party in Power\" and \"People's Front\", headed at that time by Arseniy Yatsenyuk.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://euromaidanpress.com/2014/09/11/yatseniuk-leads-new-front-line-block-which-may-unite-with-the-presidents/|title=Yatseniuk leads new \u2018front line\u2019 bloc, may unite with the President\u2019s party|last=Developed.\"|first=Government Authorities or Not Fully|date=2014-09-11|website=Euromaidan Press|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Liliia Hrynevych ran on a multi-mandate platform, and was ranked ninth in the list of the party[8].\nIn the 8th convocation Parliament (Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine), Liliia Hrynevych continued working  as a Chair of the Parliament Committee on Science and Education on developing legislative initiatives that enabled reforms in the national system of education including the academic research field.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mportal.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/117223.html|title=Verkhovna Rada Committee on Science and Education establishes workgroup to adapt draft law on science and scientific-technological activities|website=mportal.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/95554.html|title=News 2 - Parliamentary hearings entitled \u201cOn the state and legislative support to the development of science and sci-tech sphere of the state\u201d were held in the Verkhovna Rada on July 2, 2014 - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Liliia Hrynevych co-chaired an Equal Opportunities inter-factional union created in the 8th convocation Parliament in December 2014. Liliia H. was a co-author of the Draft Law on Amendments to Legal Acts of Ukraine, in particular, a gender equality legislative initiative on equal rights and opportunities for women and men in the election process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mportal.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/108231.html|title=Head of Verkhovna Rada Committee for Science and Education and co-head of Rivni Mozhlyvosti interfaction association Liliya Hrynevych takes part in conference entitled|website=mportal.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>  On 14 April 2016, the Verkhovna Rada Parliament of Ukraine appointed  a new [[Government of Ukraine|Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine]], which included Liliia Hrynevych designated as Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/news/248958685|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine appointed new Cabinet of Ministers with Volodymyr Groysman as Prime Minister of Ukraine|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nHrynevych took part in the July [[2019 Ukrainian parliamentary election]] with the party [[Ukrainian Strategy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/592382.html|title=Ukrainian Strategy Party decides to run in parliamentary elections, confirms candidates, program|website=Interfax-Ukraine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> But in the election this party did get not enough votes to clear the 5% election threshold and thus won no parliamentary seats.\n\n=== Legislative contributions ===\nLiliia Hrynevych has initiated three fundamental reforms in the education and social-humanitarian spheres: the [[External independent evaluation|External Independent Testing]], the new Law of Ukraine \u201cOn Higher Education\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zakon.rada.gov.ua/laws/anot/en/1556-18|website=zakon.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/97583.html|title=News 2 - Chairperson of the Committee on Science and Education Liliia Hrynevych participated in the meeting of chairpersons of higher educational institutions of Ukraine on matters of implementation of the Law \u201cOn Higher Education\u201d - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>,aimed at reforming the national tertiary education and \u201cNew Ukrainian School\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/education-minister-aims-build-new-school-system.html|title=Education minister aims to build new school system - Apr. 27, 2017|date=2017-04-27|website=KyivPost|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \u2013 a reform of the general secondary education defined by the Law of Ukraine \u201cOn education \u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zakon.rada.gov.ua/laws/anot/en/1556-18|website=zakon.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>  Implementation of External Independent Testing has led to equal access to education for everyone as well as a reduction in [[Corruption in Ukraine|corruption in education in Ukraine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womenua.today/en/liliya-grynevych/|title=Ms. Lilia Hrynevych - Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine|date=2018-11-26|website=\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0416\u0456\u043d\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0439 \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The Higher Education Law of Ukraine in 2014 established many innovations in higher education in Ukraine. In particular, this autonomy of universities, increased roles for student unions, changes in educational levels and academic degrees according to international practice, a new classification of universities, and new financing higher education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/article/content/ukraine-politics/rada-adopts-law-to-reform-higher-education-354346.html|title=Rada adopts law to reform higher education - Jul. 02, 2014|date=2014-07-02|website=KyivPost|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/97583.html|title=News 2 - Chairperson of the Committee on Science and Education Liliia Hrynevych participated in the meeting of chairpersons of higher educational institutions of Ukraine on matters of implementation of the Law \u201cOn Higher Education\u201d - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe main developers of higher education reform in Ukraine in general and the Higher Education law have been, in addition to Liliia Hrynevych as the Chairman of Parliamentary Committee  of Ukraine on Science and Education considered to be key include the former Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine, [[Serhiy Kvit]], and the developer of the first draft of the new law, Member of the [[National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine|National Academy of Science of Ukraine]] and [[Rector (academia)|Rector]] of [[Igor Sikorsky Kyiv Polytechnic Institute|Kyiv Polytechnic Institute]], [[Mykhailo Zghurovsky|Mykhaylo Zghurovsky]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uacrisis.org/8971-sergijj-kvit-2|title=Serhiy Kvit: The Law \u201cOn Higher Education\u201d is adopted, next are the laws \u201cOn Education\u201d and \u201cOn sciences and research-and-development activities\u201d {{!}} UACRISIS.ORG|date=2014-09-05|website=Ukraine crisis media center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Liliia Hrynevych initiated changes to the science management system, enshrined in the Law on Scientific and Technical Activities,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schiermeier|first=Quirin|date=2016-03-03|title=Conflicting laws threaten Ukrainian science|url=http://www.nature.com/news/conflicting-laws-threaten-ukrainian-science-1.19470|journal=Nature News|language=en|volume=531|issue=7592|pages=18|doi=10.1038/531018a}}</ref> which was supported by 235 parliamentarians in November 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/120487.html|title=News - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopts Law \"On scientific and scientific-technological activities\" - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The Law, in particular, defines legal, administrative and financial foundations for developments in the Scientific and Technical sphere. The Law also establishes the National Council for Science and Technology Development and the National Research Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mportal.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/117223.html|title=Verkhovna Rada Committee on Science and Education establishes workgroup to adapt draft law on science and scientific-technological activities|website=mportal.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The drafting and adoption of the Law on Education made it possible to launch \u2018The New Ukrainian School\u2019, the reform of general secondary education. It was under the chairmanship of Liliia Hrynevych, that the draft Committee prepared the Draft Law on Education and sent it to the Parliament for re-reading in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/123991.html|title=News - Elaboration of draft framework law on education being finalized - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=www.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mon.gov.ua/ua/news/usi-novivni-interview-2016-11-02-schools-to-drive-democracy-change-in-ukraine|title=\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0456\u0442\u0438 \u0456 \u043d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 - Schools to drive democracy change in Ukraine|last=Kitsoft|website=mon.gov.ua|language=ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> In 2017 the document was finalized and adopted in the second reading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/149413.html|title=News - Ukraine\u2019s law \u201cOn Education\u201d out now - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=www.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Among other achievements - the adoption of amendments to the Budget Code, and changes related to the organization of inclusive education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/News/102209.html|title=News 2 - The Committee on Science and Education discussed the issue of consideration of Committee\u2019s proposals on allocation of expenditures of the State Budget of Ukraine for 2015 - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nDuring her tenure during the 7th convocation,  Liliia Hrynevych introduced 110 Bills and resolutions, 14 of which have entered into force, and submitted 23 parliamentary inquiries. The total includes 261 amendments to Bills, of which 244 have been adopted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/pt2/reports.dep2?PERSON=15646&SKL=8|title=\u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|website=w1.c1.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/zweb2/wcadr42d?sklikannja=8&kod8011=15646|title=\u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|website=w1.c1.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> During her tenure during the 8th convocation Liliia Hrynevych has introduced 82 bills and resolutions, 37 of which have entered into force, and submitted 10 parliamentary inquiries. The total included 52 amendments to Bills of which 34 have been adopted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/pt2/reports.dep2?PERSON=15646&SKL=9|title=\u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|website=w1.c1.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://w1.c1.rada.gov.ua/pls/zweb2/wcadr42d?sklikannja=9&kod8011=15646|title=\u041e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|website=w1.c1.rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              \n\n== Activity as Minister of Education and Science of Ukraine (April 2016 -August 2019)                                                                                                                                                                      ==\nDevelopment of the education system\u00a0 \u00a0was a priority\u00a0 of\u00a0 \u00a0Volodymyr Groysman\u2019s government. Over the three years of Liliia Hrynevych\u2019s work in the Government, the consolidated budget for education\u00a0 increased from [[Ukrainian hryvnia|UAH]] 129.4 billion to [[Ukrainian hryvnia|UAH]] 246 billion. Particular attention was paid to rising the salaries in the education sector. From 2016 to 2019, teacher salaries\u00a0 increased by over 80%.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/storage/app/media/reform%20office/Ukraine_Reform_Conference_II_web.pdf|title=ref pac|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In pre-school education, the priority was to eliminate the waiting lists for enrolment to kindergartens.\u00a0 Co-operation with local authorities made it possible to shorten the wating lists from 96,000 seats in 2016 to 33,600 in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/news/novi-mozhlivosti-ta-resursi-vid-decentralizaciyi-potribno-vkladati-v-usi-sferi-rozvitku-regioniv-i-peredusim-osvitu-volodimir-grojsman|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Volodymyr Groysman: New opportunities and resources offered by decentralization need to be invested in all regional development sectors|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nLiliia Hrynevych led \"The New Ukrainian School\" (NUS) - a large-scale reform in general secondary education. Liliia Hrynevych was a co-author of the New Ukrainian School Concept, which defined the principles and objectives of the reform.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://mon.gov.ua/storage/app/media/zagalna%20serednya/Book-ENG.pdf|title=common ed pack|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/news/249248984|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Lilia Hrynevych presented a New Ukrainian School concept: We don't need to adjust the system, we should achieve new results instead|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, the Government approved the Policy Proposal to reform the general secondary education. The reform aimed at transition from a \"knowledge only school\" to a \"school of competencies\", that is the ability to use the obtained knowledge to solve practical problems and form value-based relationships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukraineworld.org/articles/reforms/ukrainian-education-new-era|title=Ukrainian Education in the New Era|website=ukraineworld.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nMinister Liliia Hrynevych suggested implementing the NUS reform in three directions: updating the education content; targeted teacher training; updating the educational environment (purchase of mobile desks, new equipment and training materials).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/education-minister-aims-build-new-school-system.html?cn-reloaded=1|title=updating school system|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n\nThe preparation and implementation of the reform began in 2017 with 100 schools in Ukraine starting to pilot the new programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukraineworld.org/articles/reforms/ukrainian-education-new-era|title=Ukrainian Education in the New Era|website=ukraineworld.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>The State Standard for Primary Education was approved In February 2018, and in September that year, all first-graders in the country began the school year in the updated learning envirnment with the\u00a0 teachers using modern teaching methods according to the new State Standard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/reformi/rozvitok-lyudskogo-kapitalu/reforma-osviti|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Education and Science Reform|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nWithin the framework of the reform, nearly 50,000 elementary school teachers, more than 11,000 Principals and Deputy Heads of educational institutions took the online and face-to-face in-service training course in blended mode.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://rakhiv-osvita.gov.ua/en/2018/02/12/%D0%BF%D1%96%D0%B4%D0%B2%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D1%8F-%D0%BA%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%BB%D1%96%D1%84%D1%96%D0%BA%D0%B0%D1%86%D1%96%D1%97-%D0%B2%D1%87%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%B5%D0%BB%D1%96%D0%B2-%D0%BF%D0%BE/|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a voluntary teacher certification was introduced aiming to identify teachers with a high professional level, innovative teaching methods and ability to share their experience. The certified teachers are payed a 20% bonus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://opinionua.com/en/2018/12/17/hobsey-about-new-ukrainian-school/The pilot certification started in 2019. https://www.tellerreport.com/news/2019-11-18---in-ukraine--announced-the-excess-number-of-school-teachers-in-the-country-.SJZA7N5x3H.html|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Government\u00a0 \u00a0subsidized the\u00a0 refurbishment of schools and\u00a0 renovation of the educational environment. The state investments in school infrastructure in 2017 amounted to UAH 1 009.5 mln, in 2018 - UAH 2 509 mln, and in 2019 - UAH 3 886.3 mln.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mon.gov.ua/ua/news/porivnyano-z-2017-m-cogo-roku-investiciyi-v-shkilnu-infrastrukturu-ta-cilovi-subvenciyi-zrosli-majzhe-v-3-razi-liliya-grinevich-pid-chas-zvitu-uryadu-za-2017-rik|title=\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0456\u0442\u0438 \u0456 \u043d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 - \u041f\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0432\u043d\u044f\u043d\u043e \u0437 2017-\u043c \u0446\u044c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u043e\u043a\u0443 \u0456\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0446\u0456\u0457 \u0432 \u0448\u043a\u0456\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0443 \u0456\u043d\u0444\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0443 \u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0456\u043b\u044c\u043e\u0432\u0456 \u0441\u0443\u0431\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0456\u0457 \u0437\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u043c\u0430\u0439\u0436\u0435 \u0432 3 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438, \u2013 \u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u043f\u0456\u0434 \u0447\u0430\u0441 \u0437\u0432\u0456\u0442\u0443 \u0423\u0440\u044f\u0434\u0443 \u0437\u0430 2017 \u0440\u0456\u043a|last=Kitsoft|website=mon.gov.ua|language=ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://mon.gov.ua/storage/app/media/Serpneva%20conferentcia/2019/mon18-06-2019conference-fin-grinevich.pdf|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe funds were allocated to the priority areas such as\u00a0 elementary school classroom transformation, equipment for the science and mathematics classrooms, the\u00a0 Ukrainian language classrooms in minority language schools,\u00a0 school sports complexes, equipment for the computer classes and the Internet access.\n\nThe learning conditions for the students in rural areas was\u00a0 a special\u00a0 concern for the Ministry. To improve these, a hub school network was created in May 2019. 785 hub schools and 1,272 hub school branches were established to build up the network in Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/default/files/2019-09-24-UkraineDecentralization.pdf|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>                                                                                                                                                                     The hub schools and their brances were assigned a priority of establishing modern science, math and computer classes, and transportation of the children from remote villages by school buses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decentralization.gov.ua/en/news/7657|title=Liliya Hrynevych: 25% of labour population in cities of oblast significance and AHs work in educational sector|last=Author|website=decentralization.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Coordination Council was established to promote collaboration between the local executive and self-governing bodies and ensure a more effective co-operation between the regional state administrations, local communities and other agencies in the course of the NUS\u00a0 implementation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/news/reforma-osviti-nadast-dodatkovih-perevag-u-virishenni-problemi-trudovoyi-migraciyi-volodimir-grojsman|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Volodymyr Groysman: Education reform will give additional preferences in solving labor migration issues|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nLiliia Hrynevychformed an ecosystem of organizations with shared concepts of the reform ideas on the partnership pedagogy, lifelong learning, competency-based and learner-centered\u00a0 approaches to learning and teaching, etc. A number of non-governmental organizations, including EdCampUkraine, EdEra, Ukrainian Step by Step Foundation (USSF), Osvitoria, Smart Osvita , BatkiSOS and others, joined this ecosystem .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edcamp.org.ua/inmediaeng|title=EdCamp Ukraine {{!}} \u0423 \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0456\u0430|website=edcamp|language=ru|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ussf.kiev.ua/|title=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u00bb|website=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u00bb|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://osvitoria.org/en/project/spivpratsya-z-ministerstvom-osvity-ukrayiny/|website=osvitoria.org|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ussf.kiev.ua/|title=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u00bb|website=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u00bb|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.smart-osvita.org/|title=Home|website=en.smart-osvita.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nTo implement the reform, Minister Liliia Hrynevych build up cooperative relationships\u00a0 with international partners. In particular, the large-scale Finnish-Ukrainian project \u201cLearning together\u201d attracted \u20ac 6 million to assist\u00a0 the implementation of the NUS reform priorities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://um.fi/news/-/asset_publisher/GRSnUwaHDPv5/content/suomi-mukana-ukrainan-koulu-uudistukses-1|title=Finland takes part in Ukrainian school reform|website=Ministry for Foreign Affairs|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Memorandum signed between the Ministry of Education and Science and the [[The Lego Group|LEGO Foundation]], made it possible to provide every Ukrainian first-grader and every class with\u00a0 free [[Lego|LEGO]] kits to support introduction of the game - and activity-based learning into the educational process.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.legofoundation.com/en/about-us/focus-geographies/ukraine/Liliia Hrynevych\u00a0 started negotiations with the World Bank to help accelerate the implementation of the primary and secondary school reform|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mon.gov.ua/eng/news/senior-specialized-school-network-formation-one-main-challenges-new-ukrainian-school-reform-and-we-are-already-looking-partners-mission-liliya-hrynevych-meeting-world-bank-representatives|title=Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine - Senior specialized school network formation is one of the main challenges of the New Ukrainian School reform, and we are already looking for partners for this mission, \u2013 Liliya Hrynevych at the meeting with the World Bank representatives|last=Kitsoft|website=mon.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nAn important area of\u00a0 the Ministry of Education and Science activity was development of inclusive education carried out in cooperation with [[Maryna Poroshenko]], the Head of the Poroshenko Charitable Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-society/2667214-inclusive-education-poroshenko-foundation-google-ukraine-education-ministry-sign-memorandum.html|title=Inclusive education: Poroshenko Foundation, Google Ukraine, Education Ministry sign Memorandum. Photos|website=www.ukrinform.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Between 2016 and 2018, the number of children with special educational needs who enrolled in secondary schools increased from 2 720<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://fsr.org.ua/sites/default/files/imce/book_print.pdf)\u00a0|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> to 12 000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukraineworld.org/articles/ukraine-explained/steady-track-inclusive-education-what-has-ukraine-done-so-far..%20561|title=Article [U/W]|website=ukraineworld.org|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Inclusive Resource Centers were set up to assist parents and teachers in creating an individual development program for each child with special educational needs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-society/2736547-561-resource-centers-for-inclusive-education-operate-in-ukraine.html|title=561 resource centers for inclusive education operate in Ukraine|website=www.ukrinform.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nAs Minister, Liliia Hrynevych launched an active [[Anti-bullying legislation|anti-bullying campaign]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://ukraine.savethechildren.net/article/how-protect-education-attack-ukrainian-context|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>The campaign found its support in the Law passed by the [[Verkhovna Rada|Parliament.]] The Law provides for counteracting bullying and introduces administrative penalties for [[bullying]] during the educational process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/rada-introduces-fines-for-bullying-in-schools.html|title=Rada introduces fines for bullying in schools {{!}} KyivPost - Ukraine's Global Voice|date=2018-12-19|website=KyivPost|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Additionally, the new Law on Education introduces the Institute of Educational Ombudsmen to ensure the students\u2019, educators\u2019, and scholars\u2019 rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opinionua.com/en/2019/09/02/serhii-horbachov/|title=Opinion {{!}} Serhii Horbachov: how Education Ombudsman service will function, whom and how it will protect and how much money is allocated for its activity|date=2019-09-02|website=Opinion|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Law on Education adopted in September 2017 laid down the main provisions of the educational reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://studyinukraine.in.ua/a-new-law-of-ukraine-on-education/|title=A new Law of Ukraine On education \u2013 Study in Ukraine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The adoption of the Law was followed by an extensive discussions of Article 7, which specifies the state language in the education system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lnu.edu.ua/en/at-lviv-university-minister-of-education-and-science-of-ukraine-tells-about-language-issue-in-law-on-education/|title=AT LVIV UNIVERSITY, MINISTER OF EDUCATION AND SCIENCE OF UKRAINE TELLS ABOUT LANGUAGE ISSUE IN LAW ON EDUCATION|website=Ivan Franko National University of Lviv|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>The state leaders of [[President of Romania|Romania]] and [[Prime Minister of Hungary|Hungary]] claimed the language article of the Law\u00a0 restricted the rights of the national minorities in Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/f1d66aac1b9c486386a138a0a0ca6b43|title=Hungary, Ukraine still at odds over Ukraine education law|date=2017-10-12|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nUkraine addressed the [[Venice Commission|European Commission for Democracy through Law (Venice Commission)]] and asked for its Opinion. In December 2017, when the Venice Commission was considering the legitimacy of Article 7, Liliia Hrynevychprovided convincing arguments and successfully defended the article \"Language of Education\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-society/2363679-ukraine-not-to-change-language-article-of-education-law-minister.html|title=Ukraine not to change language article of education law - minister|website=www.ukrinform.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>In July 2019, the [[Constitutional Court of Ukraine]] recognized the constitutionality of the Law on Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.ccu.gov.ua/en/docs/2541?order=created&sort=desc|title=2019 {{!}} Constitutional Court of Ukraine|website=web.ccu.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nPursuant to the Law on Education, the State Service for Education Quality (SSEQ)was established in 2017, which is responsible for upholding\u00a0 the state education standards and ensuring the proper education quality\u00a0 under the decentralized conditions. The basic principle of its activity is to assist educational institutions, management, teachers in improving the quality of their activities as well as\u00a0 the quality of the student learning outcomes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reformsguide.org.ua/news/the-state-service-of-education-quality-established-in-ukraine/|title=The State Service of Education Quality Established in Ukraine|date=2017-12-07|website=The Reforms Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nModernization of vocational education became an important priority of the Ministry's activities under the guidance of Liliia Hrynevych. The implementation of the investment program in 2016-2018 made it possible to create 100 training and practical centers\u00a0 for the most acute professions, where students can learn to work with modern materials, equipment and technologies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/reformi/rozvitok-lyudskogo-kapitalu/reforma-osviti|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Education and Science Reform|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe\u00a0 Agreement on financing the EU4Skills Project: Best Skills for Modern Ukraine was signed between Ukraine and the European Commission In 2018. The project attracted [[Euro|EUR]] 58 million in total and aims to\u00a0 create a network of Professional Excellence Centers,\u00a0 \u00a0including purchase of new equipment, professional development of masters and teachers, development of new curricula and standards for students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mon.gov.ua/eng/news/yevropa-nadaye-58-mln-yevro-na-modernizaciyu-profesijnoyi-osviti-v-ukrayini-v-bryusseli-pidpisano-ugodu-pro-finansuvannya-proektu-eu4skills|title=Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine - European Commission to allocate EUR 58 million to modernize vocational education in Ukraine|last=Kitsoft|website=mon.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nDuring her time in office, Minister Liliia Hrynevychmodernised the system of admission to higher education institutions.\u00a0 The admission is based on external independent testing (ZNO) results and the entire procedure is carried out online on the principle \u2018an offer goes to the best candidate\u2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chmnu.edu.ua/36733-2/|title=\u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u043f\u0440\u043e \u043f\u0456\u0434\u0441\u0443\u043c\u043a\u0438 \u0432\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u043a\u0430\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0457-2019 - \u0427\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u043d\u0456\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442 \u0456\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0456 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u041c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0438|date=2019-08-07|website=\u0427\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u043d\u0456\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442 \u0456\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0456  \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u041c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0438|language=ru|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> A mandatory standard entrance exam is introduced as secondary admission criteria for the\u00a0 Law and International Law cources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/reformi/rozvitok-lyudskogo-kapitalu/reforma-osviti|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Education and Science Reform|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The National Agency for Higher Education Quality Assurance<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://en.naqa.gov.ua/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/NAHEQA-Ukraine.pdfwas established|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, Higher education competency based standards were developed for 266 specialisms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journalist.today/en/ukraine-approves-100-modern-standards-of-higher-education-hrynevych/|title=Ukraine approves 100 modern standards of higher education \u2013 Hrynevych|last=\u0412\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0443\u043d|first=\u041a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044f\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d|date=2019-07-15|website=Journalist.today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nMinister Liliia Hrynevychpaid special attention to the reseach development at university.\u00a0For the first time the government funded a program aimed to create\u00a0 \u00a0centers for collective use of reseach equipment at higher education institutions.\u00a0 Establishment of eight\u00a0 centers at Ukrainian universities was funded by the state budget in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://ri-links2ua.eu/object/news/674In 2019, university reseach received its first basic funding.|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLiliia Hrynevychinitiated transformation of the scientific research management and financing system. In 2017\u20132018, the budgetary funding of science and research\u00a0 managed by the Ministry increased by 69%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/160685.html|title=News - \u2018Ask the Government\u2019 hour - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine|website=rada.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>The National Council for Science and TechnologyDevelopment began its work which made impact on the policy-making in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://frontnews.eu/news/en/38209|title=Hrynevych: \u201cUkraine occupies a not very high place in the international innovation rating\u201d|website=FrontNews|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Ukrainian National Research Foundation was launched to be at the forefront of the new funding system, in particular in\u00a0 provision of research grants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mon.gov.ua/eng/news/ukrayina-ta-nimechchina-domovilisya-pro-stvorennya-spilnih-centriv-peredovih-doslidzhen|title=Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine - Ukraine and Germany to establish joint centers for front-rank technologies|last=Kitsoft|website=mon.gov.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the Ministry of Education and Science first financed the access of the Ukrainian universities and research institutions\u00a0 to [[Scopus]] and the [[Web of Science]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmu.gov.ua/en/reformi/rozvitok-lyudskogo-kapitalu/reforma-osviti|title=Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine - Education and Science Reform|last=Kitsoft|website=www.kmu.gov.ua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>In 2019 these scientometric bases were available for all state budgeted universities and scientific institutions at the state budget costs.\n\nStarting in 2018, the Antarctic research at [[Vernadsky Research Base|\u201cAkademik Vernadsky\u201d]], a Ukrainian polar station,\u00a0 intensified. The National Antarctic Scientific Center\u00a0 headed by Evgen Dykyi, a marine ecology researcher and Ukrainian activist, renewed its full membership in the [[Scientific Committee on Antarctic Research]], modernized the station, provided high-quality Internet and communication; Ukrainian women joined the expedition for the first time in 20 years on the mainland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uac.gov.ua/en/women-antarctic-hryvnia-and-fully-domestic-outfit-the-24th-uae-left-for-the-akademik-vernadsky-station/|title=Women, Antarctic hryvnia and fully domestic outfit. The 24th UAE left for the Akademik Vernadsky station|last=\u041e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0430|first=\u0417\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0447|date=2019-03-26|website=UAC|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://day.kyiv.ua/en/article/topic-day/ukraine-antarctica-new-era|title=|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe National Qualification Agency, a collegial body for implementation of the state qualification policy, was established to ensure development of the National Qualification System and compliance of the learning outcomes with the relevant education levels, qualifications and the modern market requirements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://connections.etf.europa.eu/wikis/home?lang=en#!/wiki/Wf591e43b607e_4ccf_8d94_a3256a255147/page/Ukraine%20-%20NQF%20inventory|title=Welcome to Wikis|website=connections.etf.europa.eu|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAs described by Liliia herself, she met her future husband Mykhaylo during their student years, when Liliia was involved in student activities. In particular, she sang in the \u2018Cheremosh\u2019 student group.\n\nShe speaks English and Polish.\n\nAccording to politrada.com, Liliia Hryevych is most closely associated with Arseniy Yatsenyuk.[36] .Liliia Hrynevych began her political career when she joined the \"Front for Change\" party, which for a short time had her on the Board of the party. She coordinated the direction of the \"Knowledge Society\" part of a project called \"Government of Change\"  for this party, on behalf of party leader Arseniy Yatsenyuk, for whom she was the adviser on Education Affairs  for \"Front for Change\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://file.liga.net/persons/grinevich-liliya|title=\u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u0438\u043b\u0438\u044f|website=LIGA|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n\n* Badge \u201cExcellence in Education of Ukraine\u201d;\n* Badge \u201cExcellence in Capital Education\u201d;\n* Honorary diploma of Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine \"For Merit to the Ukrainian people\";\n* Order of Princess Olga 3rd Class \"for significant personal contribution to the development of national science, strengthening of scientific and technical potential of Ukraine, diligent work and high professionalism\";\n* [[Honorary title (academic)|Honorary Professor]] at [[Borys Hrinchenko Kyiv University|Borys Grinchenko Kyiv University]] \"for active civic position, personal contribution to the development of the University, creation of a holistic system of training and professional development of academic staff in Kyiv\";\n* Honorary Senator at the [[Ukrainian Catholic University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partner.kubg.edu.ua/contacts/rectorate/vice-rectors/173-liliia-hrynevych.html|title=Vice-Rectors - Liliia Hrynevych|website=partner.kubg.edu.ua|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=Rada-Bio>{{cite web |url= http://gapp.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/page/15646 |title= \u041d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 VIII \u0441\u043a\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f: \u0413\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u0456\u043b\u0456\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u0456\u0432\u043d\u0430 |language= Ukrainian |trans-title= Eighth convocation members of the Verkhovna Rada: Liliya Mykhailivna Hrynevych |publisher= [[Verkhovna Rada]] |access-date= 2015-01-07 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160927082251/http://gapp.rada.gov.ua/mps/info/page/15646 |archive-date= 2016-09-27 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=KP100709>{{cite news |url= http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/ukraine-school-system-steps-from-europe-back-to-ru-72767.html |title= Ukraine school system steps from Europe back to Russia |first= Yuriy |last= Onyshkiv |work= [[Kyiv Post]] |date= 9 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=MON140425>{{cite news|url=http://mon.gov.ua/en/regionalnews/32082-liliya-hrynevych,-chair-of-the-parliamentary-committee-for-science-and-education,-meets-with-academics-and-the-public-in-mykolayiv |title=Liliya Hrynevych, Chair of the Parliamentary Committee for Science and Education, meets with academics and the public in Mykolayiv |publisher=Ministry of Education and Science of Ukraine |date=25 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703191806/http://mon.gov.ua/en/regionalnews/32082-liliya-hrynevych%2C-chair-of-the-parliamentary-committee-for-science-and-education%2C-meets-with-academics-and-the-public-in-mykolayiv |archivedate= 3 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Ministers of Education and Sciences of Ukraine}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hrynevych, Liliya}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lviv]]\n[[Category:Seventh convocation members of the Verkhovna Rada]]\n[[Category:Eighth convocation members of the Verkhovna Rada]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:People's Front (Ukraine) politicians]]\n[[Category:Lviv Polytechnic alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Lviv alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ukrainian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ukrainian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Education and science ministers of Ukraine]]\n", "name_user": "Paul2520", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixedunrecognized language error(viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liliya_Hrynevych"}
{"title_page": "Ice boat", "text_new": "[[File:Dn nasva 0820.jpg|300px|thumb|An iceboat at the 2011 DN European Championships  in [[Nasva, Saare County|Nasva]], [[Estonia]]]]\nAn '''iceboat''' (occasionally spelled \"ice boat\") or (archaically, '''ice yacht''') is a [[boat]] or purpose-built framework similar in functional design to a [[sail boat]] but fitted with [[skis]] or runners (skates) and designed to run over [[ice]] instead of through (liquid) [[water]]. [[Ice yachting]] is the [[sport]] of [[sailing]] and racing iceboats. A related sport, [[land sailing]], utilizes a configuration with an iceboat-like fuselage or frame equipped with wheels instead of runners. Iceboats commonly used for racing are usually only for one person, but several classes of two-seat and multiple-seat iceboats are more or less common.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ice boat (Quebec).jpg|thumb|Ice boat on [[Saint Lawrence River]], [[Quebec City]], ca 1858-1860]]\n[[File:Ice yachters on Hudson River near Barrytown, NY.jpg|thumb|right|Classic iceboats on the [[Hudson River]] at [[Barrytown, New York|Barrytown, NY]]|alt=Several boats with their sails at various stages of dismantling surrounding a large vehicle with a wooded promontory behind them. In the far right upper background a portion of a bridge is visible]]\nThe history of iceboating began in Europe in areas where smooth ice was found in the bays of the Baltic Sea and the canals of the Netherlands. Initially boats were used for commerce, but soon evolved into pleasure craft\u2014\"ice yachts\". Ice sailing came to North America, where the sailing craft evolved into recreational and racing versions.\n\n=== Venues ===\nIceboating began in the 17th century as a documented means of transport on the frozen Gulf of Riga and the canals of the Netherlands into the 18th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/sports/iceboating|title=Iceboating {{!}} sport|last=Editors|first=|date=February 17, 2020|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Ice boats carried cargo on Dutch canals during the 17th century.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Spectre|first=Peter H.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/173009383|title=A mariner's book of days, 2007|date=2006|publisher=Sheridan House|year=|isbn=1-57409-226-X|location=Dobbs Ferry, NY|pages=|oclc=173009383}}</ref> \n\nThe first iceboats were introduced on New York State's Hudson River in the United States in 1790, where the practice flourished as a sport. The first recorded boat, built in 1790 by Oliver Booth of Poughkeepsie, was a square box atop three runners, the two forward runners being nailed to the box and the third acted as a rudder operated by a tiller. This type of craft was accessible to sportsmen of modest means.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://hvmag.com/things-to-do/explore-the-history-of-ice-yachting-in-the-hudson-valley/|title=Explore the History of Ice Yachting in the Hudson Valley|last=Levine|first=David|date=|website=www.hvmag.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-19th century, two \"ice yachting\" clubs had formed, the Poughkeepsie Ice Yacht Club (1865) and the Hudson River Ice Yacht Club (1870), where wealthy boat owners sailed large iceboats with up to seven crew members. Boats were as long as {{Convert|69|ft|m|abbr=}} and sailed as fast as {{Convert|107|mi/h|km/h|abbr=}}, a record exceeding any other conveyance in 1885, set by the ''[[Icicle (yacht)|Icicle]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first American Challenge Pennant occurred in 1881 on the Hudson river with five ice-yacht clubs competing. Races were sailed five times around a triangular course with one-mile legs, two of which were to windward. Iceboats were divided into four classes with sail areas ranging from less than 300 square feet to over 600 square feet.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1911|isbn=|editor-last=Chisholm|editor-first=Hugh|edition=11|volume=14|location=|pages=241\u2013242|chapter=Ice-Yachting}}</ref>\n\nBy the beginning of the 20th century, iceboating had spread to Minnesota ([[Lake Minnetonka]] and [[White Bear Lake, Minnesota|White Bear Lake]]), Wisconsin ([[Lake Winnebago]] and [[Lake Pepin]]) and venues in Maine and Vermont. In Canada, there were venues on [[Lake Ontario]] (Kingston) and the [[Saint Lawrence River]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nA European ice sailing club formed first in Sweden (1901), followed by the European Ice Yachting Union, which formed in 1928 with member states Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia, Sweden, Austria, and Germany.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Evolution of design ===\n[[File:Vinckboons Landscape with skaters.jpg|thumb|Dutch Iceboats, 17th century]]\n[[File:IJszeilen op de Gouwzee Weeknummer 38-52 - Open Beelden - 50860.ogv|thumb|right|Ice sailing in the Netherlands in 1938.]]\n17th-century Dutch ice-yachts consisted of flat-bottomed sailboats atop a cross-wise plank, resting on outboard metal runners, which carried the bulk of the weight of the craft. At the stern was a steering runner, attached to a rudder-like structure. to which are affixed four steel runners, one each at bow, stern and each end of the planking. These boats used conventional gaff mainsails and jibs, attached to the mast by travellers. A tiller or wheel stern controls the steering runner.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the 19th century iceboats evolved into a box, riding on cross-pieces, supported by runners. These \"stern-steerer\" iceboats were generally rigged as [[sloop]]s, with a [[jib]] sail forward of the mast, although the [[catboat]] style with a single sail was also used.<ref name=\":03\" /> In 1879 the archetypical Hudson River iceboat began to emerge. <nowiki>''</nowiki>Robert Scott<nowiki>''</nowiki>, designed and built by H. Relyea, had a single backbone and wire guy-ropes. The mast on subsequent boats were stepped further forward than in the past with shortened jibs were shortened and the center of effort and resistance brought into balance, aligning both with the main runners.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danielfisher/2014/03/07/as-the-hudson-river-freezes-over-classic-ice-yachts-emerge/|title=As The Hudson River Freezes, Classic Ice Yachts Emerge|last=Fisher|first=Daniel|date=March 7, 2014|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The shallow steering-box became elliptical.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the early 1900s some smaller iceboats, called ''scooters'', were designed to traverse both ice and water with a shallow, oval {{Convert|15*5|ft|m|abbr=}} hull on fixed runners. These sailing craft were steered by manipulating the sails, there being no rudder.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe traditional stern-steerer boats were largely replaced by front steering boats in the 1930s, following the development of this style by Walter Beauvois of [[Williams Bay, Wisconsin]] in a boat named the ''Beau Skeeter''.<ref name=\":4\" /> This boat led to the \"Skeeter\" class, and the ''Skeeter Ice Boat Club'' formed on [[Geneva Lake]], Wisconsin. The Skeeter class adopted the logo of a mosquito on their sail, and has evolved into a very efficient aerodynamically clean machine. The Skeeter class is limited to just {{convert|75|sqft|m2}} of sail.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Andrews|first=Candice Gaukel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OlmGjEU7qU4C&pg=PA152&dq=%22skeeter+iceboat%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjWs8eQoOnoAhVPlnIEHQMiCZIQ6AEwAHoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=skeeter&f=false|title=Great Wisconsin Winter Weekends|date=2006|publisher=Big Earth Publishing|year=|isbn=978-1-931599-71-9|location=|pages=152|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1937, The [[Detroit News]] sponsored a new home-buildable ice boat design, which became the [[International DN]]. In 1968 Dick Slates of [[Pewaukee, Wisconsin]] designed and built the ''Nite'' with two wooden prototypes. The design was refined and fiberglass production began in 1970.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Speed==\n[[File:Ice boat apparent wind on different points of sail.jpg|thumb|Diagram of apparent wind on an iceboat on different points of sail\u2014the sail is close-hauled on each point of sail.]]\nIceboats designs dating from the mid 20th century onwards typically consist of a triangular or cross-shaped frame, supported by three skate blades called \"runners\", with the steering runner in front. Runners are made of iron or steel and sharpened to a fine edge, most often cut to an angled edge of 90 degrees, which holds onto the ice, preventing slippage sideways from the lateral force of the wind developed by the sails, as they develop [[Forces on sails|propulsive lift]]. Given their low forward resistance, iceboats can sail up to ten times the speed of the true wind. Because the speed of the iceboat is so much greater than the true wind velocity, the apparent wind is only a few degrees from the direction of travel on most [[Point of sail|points of sail]].<ref>See page 204 of {{cite book\n |last = Bethwaite\n |first = Frank\n |title = High Performance Sailing\n |publisher = Adlard Coles Nautical\n |year = 2007\n |isbn = 978-0-7136-6704-2}}</ref>\n\n=== Attainable speeds ===\nDifferent classes of iceboat can achieve speeds, as follow. \n\n* [[International DN]]: {{convert|48-59|knots|km/h mph|abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Boat_Speed\">{{Citation\n | first = Bob\n | last = Dill\n | contribution = Sailing Yacht Design for Maximum Speed\n | contribution-url = http://static1.1.sqspcdn.com/static/f/572109/24503675/1394724903587/Sailing+Yacht+Design+for+Maximum+Speed.pdf?token=5pzNaaWIFu%2F7e3pN5RiQ2e6MmmM%3D\n | title = The 16th Chesapeake Sailing Yacht Symposium\n | date = March 2003\n | pages =\n | place = Anapolis\n | publisher = SNAME\n | url = http://www.sname.org/chesapeakesailingyachtsymposiumcsys/pastpapers/16thcsys }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dill|first=Bob|date=February 2004|title=Putting Numbers on Iceboat Performance|url=https://www.nalsa.org/Articles/Cetus/Iceboat%20Sailing%20Performance-Cetus.pdf|journal=International DN Ice Yacht Racing Association Newsletter|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n* Classic iceboats and Skeeters: {{convert|90-130|knots|km/h mph|abbr=}}. Record: ''Das Boot'', {{convert|135.5|knots|km/h mph|abbr=}}.<ref name=\":4\" /> Record: classic iceboat, ''Debutaunte'', {{convert|124|knots|km/h mph}}.<ref name=\"Boat_Speed\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Smith|first=Doug|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mfwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=dn+ice+boat+speed+record&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-luSX8-roAhU8knIEHW7eA2AQ6AEwA3oECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=dn%20ice%20boat%20speed%20record&f=false|title=Sailing on slivers of steel|date=January-February 2004|work=Scouting|publisher=Boy Scouts of America, Inc.|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=18-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Race courses ===\nBecause of the high boat speeds, iceboat race courses are established around fixed marks which are to be rounded in a one-way route, enhancing boat-to-boat traffic safety. The courses are a straight line [[upwind]] and [[downwind]], which necessitates [[Tacking (sailing)|tacking]] upwind and [[Jibe|jibing]] downwind.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Classes==\n[[File:Regaty bojerowe w klasie DN na Jeziorze Du\u017cym w \u017bninie.jpg|thumb|DN class iceboats at the start of a race in [[Znin]], [[Poland]]]]\n[[File:JWC-JEC 2019 IceOptimists.jpg|thumb|IceOptimists]]\n[[File:SIK-N157 14.jpg|thumb|Monotype XV]]\n\n=== International DN ===\nThe [[International DN]] class is the most popular class in both North America and Europe. It is a one-person wood boat twelve feet long with a cross-plank eight feet long that carries a mast {{convert|16|ft|m}} high. Modern competitive DNs use flexible masts commonly made of composite materials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227121944/https://ice.idniyra.org/|title=IDNIYRA {{!}} International DN Ice Yacht Racing Association|date=2017-12-27|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The DN 60 derives its name from request published in the late 1930s by [[The Detroit News|''The Detroit News'']] for a high-performance, inexpensive, home-built iceboat design. Modern DNs share many one-design features with the original boat, including the basic aerodynamic fuselage design, runner configurations and {{convert|60|sqft|m2}} of high-performance sail.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Staff|first=|date=January 1982|title=Endless winter, the iceboater's dream|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mgMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA59&dq=skeeter+ice+boat&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjB0fvbnOnoAhWohHIEHQrjBWUQ6AEwAnoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=skeeter%20ice%20boat&f=false|journal=Changing Times-The Kiplinger Magazine|volume=36|issue=1|pages=58-9|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== IceOptimist ===\nThe IceOptimist is a youth iceboat class that uses the sails and the rig of the [[Optimist (dinghy)|International Optimist dinghy]]. The first design was built in [[Estonia]] in 1978, with scaled-down elements of a [[International DN|DN]]. In [[2002]], the class was registered under the guardianship of IDNIYRA Europe with the permission of IODA. World and European Championships are sailed each winter with a fleet of approximately 40 racers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idniyra.eu/juniors/|title=ICE OPTI and DN JUNIOR \u2013 IDNIYRA \u2013 Europe|website=idniyra.eu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Monotype XV ===\nThe Monotype XV is a class of iceboat based on a 1932 design by Estonian, Erik von Holst. It may be single or double-handed. The [[One-Design|one-design]] class is built according to close specifications, little changed since the 1930s. It is the largest one-design iceboat class in Europe and the only double-handed iceboat class for which there are international championships. The {{Convert|205|kg|lb|abbr=|adj=on}} is {{Convert|7.5*4.2|m|ft|abbr=}} in length and width with a {{Convert|7.2|m|ft|abbr=|adj=on}} high mast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iceboat.org/2019/03/04/monotype-xv-european-championship/|title=Monotype XV European Championship|last=Whitehorse|first=Deb|date=2019-03-04|website=iceboat.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Skeeter ===\nThe Skeeter class is divided into sub-classes (A, B and C) all of which are limited to {{convert|75|sqft|m2}} of sail area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iceboat.org/regattas/internationalskeeterassociation/|title=International Skeeter Association|website=iceboat.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> ''A-class'' boats may be single or two-place tandem with a mast that does not exceed {{Convert|28.5|ft|m|abbr=}}. They may incorporate carbon fiber construction.<ref name=\":3\" /> ''B-class'' boats have seats for two (side by side). ''C-class'' skeeters may be single or two-place tandem with a mast that does not exceed {{Convert|20.25|ft|m|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://139655-585885-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/ISARules.pdf|title=General rules and regulations of the International Skeeter Association|last=Class committee|first=|date=October 16, 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[Sail boat]]\n* [[Sailing]]\n* [[Land sailing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Iceboats}}\n\n{{Application of wind energy}}\n{{Ice}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ice Boat}}\n[[Category:Ice yachting]]\n[[Category:Sailboat types]]\n[[Category:Racing vehicles]]\n[[Category:Human-powered watercraft]]\n\n[[de:Eissegeln]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Dn nasva 0820.jpg|300px|thumb|An iceboat at the 2011 DN European Championships  in [[Nasva, Saare County|Nasva]], [[Estonia]]]]\nAn '''iceboat''' (occasionally spelled \"ice boat\") or (archaically, '''ice yacht''') is a [[boat]] or purpose-built framework similar in functional design to a [[sail boat]] but fitted with [[skis]] or runners (skates) and designed to run over [[ice]] instead of through (liquid) [[water]]. [[Ice yachting]] is the [[sport]] of [[sailing]] and racing iceboats. A related sport, [[land sailing]], utilizes a configuration with an iceboat-like fuselage or frame equipped with wheels instead of runners. Iceboats commonly used for racing are usually only for one person, but several classes of two-seat and multiple-seat iceboats are more or less common.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ice boat (Quebec).jpg|thumb|Ice boat on [[Saint Lawrence River]], [[Quebec City]], ca 1858-1860]]\n[[File:Ice yachters on Hudson River near Barrytown, NY.jpg|thumb|right|Classic iceboats on the [[Hudson River]] at [[Barrytown, New York|Barrytown, NY]]|alt=Several boats with their sails at various stages of dismantling surrounding a large vehicle with a wooded promontory behind them. In the far right upper background a portion of a bridge is visible]]\nThe history of iceboating began in Europe in areas where smooth ice was found in the bays of the Baltic Sea and the canals of the Netherlands. Initially boats were used for commerce, but soon evolved into pleasure craft\u2014\"ice yachts\". Ice sailing came to North America, where the sailing craft evolved into recreational and racing versions.\n\n=== Venues ===\nIceboating began in the 17th century as a documented means of transport on the frozen Gulf of Riga and the canals of the Netherlands into the 18th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/sports/iceboating|title=Iceboating {{!}} sport|last=Editors|first=|date=February 17, 2020|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Ice boats carried cargo on Dutch canals during the 17th century.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Spectre|first=Peter H.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/173009383|title=A mariner's book of days, 2007|date=2006|publisher=Sheridan House|year=|isbn=1-57409-226-X|location=Dobbs Ferry, NY|pages=|oclc=173009383}}</ref> \n\nThe first iceboats were introduced on New York State's Hudson River in the United States in 1790, where the practice flourished as a sport. The first recorded boat, built in 1790 by Oliver Booth of Poughkeepsie, was a square box atop three runners, the two forward runners being nailed to the box and the third acted as a rudder operated by a tiller. This type of craft was accessible to sportsmen of modest means.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://hvmag.com/things-to-do/explore-the-history-of-ice-yachting-in-the-hudson-valley/|title=Explore the History of Ice Yachting in the Hudson Valley|last=Levine|first=David|date=|website=www.hvmag.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-19th century, two \"ice yachting\" clubs had formed, the Poughkeepsie Ice Yacht Club (1865) and the Hudson River Ice Yacht Club (1870), where wealthy boat owners sailed large iceboats with up to seven crew members. Boats were as long as {{Convert|69|ft|m|abbr=}} and sailed as fast as {{Convert|107|mi/h|km/h|abbr=}}, a record exceeding any other conveyance in 1885, set by the ''[[Icicle (yacht)|Icicle]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first American Challenge Pennant occurred in 1881 on the Hudson river with five ice-yacht clubs competing. Races were sailed five times around a triangular course with one-mile legs, two of which were to windward. Iceboats were divided into four classes with sail areas ranging from less than 300 square feet to over 600 square feet.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1911|isbn=|editor-last=Chisholm|editor-first=Hugh|edition=11|volume=14|location=|pages=241\u2013242|chapter=Ice-Yachting}}</ref>\n\nBy the beginning of the 20th century, iceboating had spread to Minnesota ([[Lake Minnetonka]] and [[White Bear Lake, Minnesota|White Bear Lake]]), Wisconsin ([[Lake Winnebago]] and [[Lake Pepin]]) and venues in Maine and Vermont. In Canada, there were venues on [[Lake Ontario]] (Kingston) and the [[Saint Lawrence River]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nA European ice sailing club formed first in Sweden (1901), followed by the European Ice Yachting Union, which formed in 1928 with member states Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia, Sweden, Austria, and Germany.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Evolution of design ===\n[[File:Vinckboons Landscape with skaters.jpg|thumb|Dutch Iceboats, 17th century]]\n[[File:IJszeilen op de Gouwzee Weeknummer 38-52 - Open Beelden - 50860.ogv|thumb|right|Ice sailing in the Netherlands in 1938.]]\n17th-century Dutch ice-yachts consisted of flat-bottomed sailboats atop a cross-wise plank, resting on outboard metal runners, which carried the bulk of the weight of the craft. At the stern was a steering runner, attached to a rudder-like structure. to which are affixed four steel runners, one each at bow, stern and each end of the planking. These boats used conventional gaff mainsails and jibs, attached to the mast by travellers. A tiller or wheel stern controls the steering runner.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the 19th century iceboats evolved into a box, riding on cross-pieces, supported by runners. These \"stern-steerer\" iceboats were generally rigged as [[sloop]]s, with a [[jib]] sail forward of the mast, although the [[catboat]] style with a single sail was also used.<ref name=\":03\" /> In 1879 the archetypical Hudson River iceboat began to emerge. <nowiki>''</nowiki>Robert Scott<nowiki>''</nowiki>, designed and built by H. Relyea, had a single backbone and wire guy-ropes. The mast on subsequent boats were stepped further forward than in the past with shortened jibs were shortened and the center of effort and resistance brought into balance, aligning both with the main runners.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danielfisher/2014/03/07/as-the-hudson-river-freezes-over-classic-ice-yachts-emerge/|title=As The Hudson River Freezes, Classic Ice Yachts Emerge|last=Fisher|first=Daniel|date=March 7, 2014|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The shallow steering-box became elliptical.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the early 1900s some smaller iceboats, called ''scooters'', were designed to traverse both ice and water with a shallow, oval {{Convert|15*5|ft|m|abbr=}} hull on fixed runners. These sailing craft were steered by manipulating the sails, there being no rudder.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe traditional stern-steerer boats were largely replaced by front steering boats in the 1930s, following the development of this style by Walter Beauvois of [[Williams Bay, Wisconsin]] in a boat named the ''Beau Skeeter''.<ref name=\":4\" /> This boat led to the \"Skeeter\" class, and the ''Skeeter Ice Boat Club'' formed on [[Geneva Lake]], Wisconsin. The Skeeter class adopted the logo of a mosquito on their sail, and has evolved into a very efficient aerodynamically clean machine. The Skeeter class is limited to just {{convert|75|sqft|m2}} of sail.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Andrews|first=Candice Gaukel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OlmGjEU7qU4C&pg=PA152&dq=%22skeeter+iceboat%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjWs8eQoOnoAhVPlnIEHQMiCZIQ6AEwAHoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=skeeter&f=false|title=Great Wisconsin Winter Weekends|date=2006|publisher=Big Earth Publishing|year=|isbn=978-1-931599-71-9|location=|pages=152|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1937, The [[Detroit News]] sponsored a new home-buildable ice boat design, which became the [[International DN]]. In 1968 Dick Slates of [[Pewaukee, Wisconsin]] designed and built the ''Nite'' with two wooden prototypes. The design was refined and fiberglass production began in 1970.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Speed==\n[[File:Ice boat apparent wind on different points of sail.jpg|thumb|Diagram of apparent wind on an iceboat on different points of sail\u2014the sail is close-hauled on each point of sail.]]\nIceboats designs dating from the mid 20th century onwards typically consist of a triangular or cross-shaped frame, supported by three skate blades called \"runners\", with the steering runner in front. Runners are made of iron or steel and sharpened to a fine edge, most often cut to an angled edge of 90 degrees, which holds onto the ice, preventing slippage sideways from the lateral force of the wind developed by the sails, as they develop [[Forces on sails|propulsive lift]]. Given their low forward resistance, iceboats can sail up to ten times the speed of the true wind. Because the speed of the iceboat is so much greater than the true wind velocity, the apparent wind is only a few degrees from the direction of travel on most [[Point of sail|points of sail]].<ref>See page 204 of {{cite book\n |last = Bethwaite\n |first = Frank\n |title = High Performance Sailing\n |publisher = Adlard Coles Nautical\n |year = 2007\n |isbn = 978-0-7136-6704-2}}</ref>\n\n=== Attainable speeds ===\nDifferent classes of iceboat can achieve speeds, as follow. \n\n* [[International DN]]: {{convert|48-59|knots|km/h mph|abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Boat_Speed\">{{Citation\n | first = Bob\n | last = Dill\n | contribution = Sailing Yacht Design for Maximum Speed\n | contribution-url = http://static1.1.sqspcdn.com/static/f/572109/24503675/1394724903587/Sailing+Yacht+Design+for+Maximum+Speed.pdf?token=5pzNaaWIFu%2F7e3pN5RiQ2e6MmmM%3D\n | title = The 16th Chesapeake Sailing Yacht Symposium\n | date = March 2003\n | pages =\n | place = Anapolis\n | publisher = SNAME\n | url = http://www.sname.org/chesapeakesailingyachtsymposiumcsys/pastpapers/16thcsys }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dill|first=Bob|date=February 2004|title=Putting Numbers on Iceboat Performance|url=https://www.nalsa.org/Articles/Cetus/Iceboat%20Sailing%20Performance-Cetus.pdf|journal=International DN Ice Yacht Racing Association Newsletter|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n* Classic iceboats and Skeeters: {{convert|90-130|knots|km/h mph|abbr=}}. Record: ''Das Boot'', {{convert|135.5|knots|km/h mph|abbr=}}.<ref name=\":4\" /> Record: classic iceboat, ''Debutaunte'', {{convert|124|knots|km/h mph}}.<ref name=\"Boat_Speed\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Smith|first=Doug|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mfwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=dn+ice+boat+speed+record&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-luSX8-roAhU8knIEHW7eA2AQ6AEwA3oECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=dn%20ice%20boat%20speed%20record&f=false|title=Sailing on slivers of steel|date=January-February 2004|work=Scouting|publisher=Boy Scouts of America, Inc.|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=18-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Race courses ===\nBecause of the high boat speeds, iceboat race courses are established around fixed marks which are to be rounded in a one-way route, enhancing boat-to-boat traffic safety. The courses are a straight line [[upwind]] and [[downwind]], which necessitates [[Tacking (sailing)|tacking]] upwind and [[Jibe|jibing]] downwind.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Classes==\n[[File:Regaty bojerowe w klasie DN na Jeziorze Du\u017cym w \u017bninie.jpg|thumb|DN class iceboats at the start of a race in [[Znin]], [[Poland]]]]\n[[File:JWC-JEC 2019 IceOptimists.jpg|thumb|IceOptimists]]\n[[File:SIK-N157 14.jpg|thumb|Monotype XV]]\n\n=== International DN ===\nThe [[International DN]] class is the most popular class in both North America and Europe. It is a one-person wood boat twelve feet long with a cross-plank eight feet long that carries a mast {{convert|16|ft|m}} high. Modern competitive DNs use flexible masts commonly made of composite materials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227121944/https://ice.idniyra.org/|title=IDNIYRA {{!}} International DN Ice Yacht Racing Association|date=2017-12-27|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The DN 60 derives its name from request published in the late 1930s by [[The Detroit News|''The Detroit News'']] for a high-performance, inexpensive, home-built iceboat design. Modern DNs share many one-design features with the original boat, including the basic aerodynamic fuselage design, runner configurations and {{convert|60|sqft|m2}} of high-performance sail.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Staff|first=|date=January 1982|title=Endless winter, the iceboater's dream|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mgMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA59&dq=skeeter+ice+boat&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjB0fvbnOnoAhWohHIEHQrjBWUQ6AEwAnoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=skeeter%20ice%20boat&f=false|journal=Changing Times-The Kiplinger Magazine|volume=36|issue=1|pages=58-9|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== IceOptimist ===\nThe IceOptimist is a youth iceboat class that uses the sails and the rig of the [[Optimist (dinghy)|International Optimist dinghy]]. The first design was built in [[Estonia]] in 1978, with scaled-down elements of a [[International DN|DN]]. In [[2002]], the class was registered under the guardianship of IDNIYRA Europe with the permission of IODA. World and European Championships are sailed each winter with a fleet of approximately 40 racers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idniyra.eu/juniors/|title=ICE OPTI and DN JUNIOR \u2013 IDNIYRA \u2013 Europe|website=idniyra.eu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Monotype XV ===\nThe Monotype XV is a class of iceboat based on a 1932 design by Estonian, Erik von Holst. It may be single or double-handed. The [[One-Design|one-design]] class is built according to close specifications, little changed since the 1930s. It is the largest one-design iceboat class in Europe and the only double-handed iceboat class for which there are international championships. The {{Convert|205|kg|lb|abbr=|adj=on}} is {{Convert|7.5*4.2|m|ft|abbr=}} in length and width with a {{Convert|7.2|m|ft|abbr=|adj=on}} high mast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iceboat.org/2019/03/04/monotype-xv-european-championship/|title=Monotype XV European Championship|last=Whitehorse|first=Deb|date=2019-03-04|website=iceboat.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Skeeter ===\nThe Skeeter class is divided into sub-classes (A, B and C) all of which are limited to {{convert|75|sqft|m2}} of sail area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iceboat.org/regattas/internationalskeeterassociation/|title=International Skeeter Association|website=iceboat.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> ''A-class'' boats may be single or two-place tandem with a mast that does not exceed {{Convert|28.5|ft|m|abbr=}}. They may incorporate carbon fiber construction.<ref name=\":3\" /> ''B-class'' boats have seats for two (side by side). ''C-class'' skeeters may be single or two-place tandem with a mast that does not exceed {{Convert|20.25|ft|m|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://139655-585885-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/ISARules.pdf|title=General rules and regulations of the International Skeeter Association|last=Class committee|first=|date=October 16, 2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n\n<br />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[Sail boat]]\n* [[Sailing]]\n* [[Land sailing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Iceboats}}\n\n{{Application of wind energy}}\n{{Ice}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ice Boat}}\n[[Category:Ice yachting]]\n[[Category:Sailboat types]]\n[[Category:Racing vehicles]]\n[[Category:Human-powered watercraft]]\n\n[[de:Eissegeln]]\n", "name_user": "HopsonRoad", "label": "safe", "comment": "CE.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ice_boat"}
{"title_page": "AVR (2020 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 film by Arindam Sharma}}\n{{EngvarB|date = April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = AVR\n| image          = Poster_Of_AVR_Assamese_Film.jpg\n| director       = [[Arindam Sharma]]\n| producer       = Brojendra Nath Sarma\n| writer         = Arindam Sharma\n| starring       = {{unbulleted list|[[Arnab Ayan]]|[[Ajay Barman]]|Niha Rani Das|Bikash Borah|}}\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Kailash Duarah\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2020|10|23|}}\n| country        = India\n| language       = Assamese\n| studio         = Krishna Kraft Productions \n}}\n'''''AVR : Advik Vs. Ray''''' is an upcoming 2020 Indian [[Assamese cinema|Assamese-language]] [[Super Hero|science fiction]] [[action film]] written and directed by [[Arindam Sharma]] and starring [[Arnab Ayan]] and Niha Rani Das in the lead roles and [[Ajay Barman]] in lead villain. The film is produced by Brojendra Nath Sarma under Krishna Kraft Productions.\n\nThe film\u2019s cinematography is done by Kailash Duarah. Its a film having 600 VFX shots. AVR is scheduled to be released on 23rd October 2020.<ref>1.{{Cite web|url=https://rupaliparda.com/archives/12430|title=\u0986\u09b9\u09bf \u0986\u099b\u09c7 \"AVR: Advik Vs Ray\"- \u098f\u0996\u09a8 \u0985\u09b8\u09ae\u09c0\u09af\u09bc\u09be \"\u099a\u09c1\u09aa\u09be\u09f0\u09b9\u09bf\u09f0\u09cb\" \u099b\u09ac\u09bf\u0983|website=rupaliparda.com}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n\n* Arnab Ayan as Advik, Pranay\n* [[Ajay Barman]] as Ray, Dr.Roy\n* Niha Rani Das as Sneha (Pranay's Wife)\n* Bikash Borah as Pratik (Pranay's Brother)\n* Nilutpal Borah as Nill (Pranay's Friend)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n2.{{Cite web|url=https://assamtimespost.com/?p=17846|title=\u0986\u09b9\u09bf \u0986\u099b\u09c7 \u0985\u09b8\u09ae\u09c0\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09a4 \u098f\u0996\u09a8 \"\u099a\u09c1\u09aa\u09be\u09f0\u09b9\u09bf\u09f0\u09cb' \u099a\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09ae\u09be\"\u0964 \u09a8\u09f1\u09b